1
00:00:07,750 --> 00:00:10,750
[uplifting music playing]

2
00:00:32,583 --> 00:00:33,583
[Nate] God.

3
00:00:34,416 --> 00:00:38,666
I get tuna every time and I hate tuna.
You know I hate tuna, but I just... get it.

4
00:00:38,750 --> 00:00:40,642
- It's like... What'd you get?
- [Fielding] Italian.

5
00:00:40,666 --> 00:00:43,125
See, that... That's a good choice.
Italian is a good sandwich.

6
00:00:44,208 --> 00:00:46,208
- [man] What's up, babe?
- [Nate] Oh, no.

7
00:00:47,416 --> 00:00:49,375
Fields, whatever you do,
don't look to your left.

8
00:00:51,958 --> 00:00:53,333
[sighs] Oh, no way.

9
00:00:54,375 --> 00:00:55,375
[Nate] Sorry, pal.

10
00:00:57,541 --> 00:01:01,375
Just one week into senior year.
How'd she just leave me?

11
00:01:01,458 --> 00:01:02,708
Apparently by text.

12
00:01:04,041 --> 00:01:05,041
[sighs]

13
00:01:05,125 --> 00:01:06,583
I... I can't eat this.

14
00:01:07,458 --> 00:01:08,625
- I feel so alone.
- Yeah.

15
00:01:08,708 --> 00:01:10,916
"Loneliness and the feeling
of being unwanted

16
00:01:11,000 --> 00:01:12,500
is the most terrible poverty."

17
00:01:12,583 --> 00:01:15,583
Mother Teresa, who, by the way,
I guarantee you was never dumped.

18
00:01:15,666 --> 00:01:20,166
I mean, seriously, you dump her,
that is one-way ticket downstairs.

19
00:01:20,250 --> 00:01:21,791
Shh! Is that the guy?

20
00:01:22,291 --> 00:01:23,333
[Nate] Who?

21
00:01:24,041 --> 00:01:27,375
- She left me for a Frisbee guy?
- You're a Frisbee guy.

22
00:01:27,458 --> 00:01:29,138
[Fielding] No, not like him. He's, like...

23
00:01:30,500 --> 00:01:31,500
shirtless.

24
00:01:32,500 --> 00:01:33,666
He looks great.

25
00:01:34,416 --> 00:01:35,500
- Thank you.
- Well.

26
00:01:36,083 --> 00:01:37,583
I think that tonight,

27
00:01:37,666 --> 00:01:39,458
we should go down to the Bobcat,

28
00:01:39,541 --> 00:01:42,375
get some drinks, get some wings,

29
00:01:42,458 --> 00:01:44,583
forget about Claire and this Adonis.

30
00:01:45,833 --> 00:01:47,208
You...

31
00:01:47,291 --> 00:01:48,291
Where'd you go?

32
00:01:50,500 --> 00:01:52,583
You aren't listening.

33
00:01:54,666 --> 00:01:55,833
Let's go to the pound.

34
00:01:55,916 --> 00:01:57,625
- [dogs barking]
- This is a mistake.

35
00:01:57,708 --> 00:01:59,875
Okay, I have love to give,
and Claire doesn't want it.

36
00:01:59,958 --> 00:02:02,583
I love you, babe. Me, I do.
Can we go now, please?

37
00:02:02,666 --> 00:02:03,791
I am getting a dog.

38
00:02:03,875 --> 00:02:05,708
When was the last time you showered?

39
00:02:07,500 --> 00:02:08,500
It was a Tuesday.

40
00:02:08,583 --> 00:02:12,875
Listen, dogs, they need shots.
They need food and water every day.

41
00:02:12,958 --> 00:02:14,000
- Okay?
- Yeah.

42
00:02:14,083 --> 00:02:15,083
You are just...

43
00:02:16,041 --> 00:02:18,250
You're ill-equipped.
I'm sorry. You just are.

44
00:02:19,500 --> 00:02:21,625
- "What is man without the beasts?"
- Oh, no.

45
00:02:21,708 --> 00:02:23,028
"For if all the beasts were gone,

46
00:02:23,083 --> 00:02:27,000
man would die
of a great loneliness of the spirit."

47
00:02:27,083 --> 00:02:29,517
- It's Chief Seattle.
- I know it's Chief Seattle. I know it is.

48
00:02:29,541 --> 00:02:32,791
Just listen. A B-minus
in Native American studies

49
00:02:32,875 --> 00:02:34,875
does not qualify you
to care for an animal.

50
00:02:34,958 --> 00:02:38,041
- Also, please don't ever do that again.
- Why?

51
00:02:38,125 --> 00:02:41,458
It's very off-putting when you quote
smart dead guys back at me.

52
00:02:41,541 --> 00:02:43,458
That's my thing.
Philosophical arts, my thing.

53
00:02:43,541 --> 00:02:44,875
- You know it.
- Okay.

54
00:02:45,458 --> 00:02:48,208
[dog yapping]

55
00:02:50,500 --> 00:02:51,375
Oh, no.

56
00:02:51,458 --> 00:02:52,791
Well, hey!

57
00:02:52,875 --> 00:02:54,583
[dog yapping and whining]

58
00:02:55,625 --> 00:02:57,041
What's up, pup?

59
00:02:57,125 --> 00:02:59,125
[emotional music playing]

60
00:03:02,333 --> 00:03:03,333
I love him.

61
00:03:05,458 --> 00:03:06,625
[whining]

62
00:03:06,708 --> 00:03:08,041
[Fielding] And he loves me.

63
00:03:09,083 --> 00:03:10,083
[Fielding chuckles]

64
00:03:14,750 --> 00:03:16,208
Whoop! That's a big bag.

65
00:03:16,791 --> 00:03:20,541
All right. Oh, and I need him to imprint
on me, so don't, like, bond with him.

66
00:03:20,625 --> 00:03:21,750
Done and done.

67
00:03:21,833 --> 00:03:24,541
You know what, little buddy?
I am gonna find the perfect song

68
00:03:24,625 --> 00:03:26,083
for our first car ride together.

69
00:03:30,333 --> 00:03:31,875
Why is it so warm in here?

70
00:03:31,958 --> 00:03:34,208
I told you, the AC is still broken.

71
00:03:34,958 --> 00:03:36,666
- Oh, my God!
- Don't scare him.

72
00:03:36,750 --> 00:03:38,458
- He's peeing on me!
- Whoa! Oh, yeah.

73
00:03:38,541 --> 00:03:40,601
- Fields, take your dog right now.
- I don't want him!

74
00:03:40,625 --> 00:03:41,833
- I don't want him!
- Hold on!

75
00:03:41,916 --> 00:03:43,316
Take him right now. I swear to God.

76
00:03:43,375 --> 00:03:46,250
Listen, I don't want his first
five minutes with us to be traumatizing,

77
00:03:46,333 --> 00:03:48,583
so just, like, let him do his thing.

78
00:03:48,666 --> 00:03:50,958
[urinating continues]

79
00:03:51,041 --> 00:03:52,881
This is the worst thing
that has ever happened.

80
00:03:52,916 --> 00:03:54,708
- He likes you.
- [urinating continues]

81
00:03:55,291 --> 00:03:56,500
Why is there so much?

82
00:03:56,583 --> 00:03:58,458
- [urinating continues]
- I don't...

83
00:03:59,166 --> 00:04:00,666
Yeah. Wow. All right.

84
00:04:01,166 --> 00:04:02,583
Maybe we shouldn't look.

85
00:04:02,666 --> 00:04:04,666
[urinating continues]

86
00:04:05,875 --> 00:04:07,083
[urinating stops]

87
00:04:07,166 --> 00:04:08,916
Oh! Yeah! Okay.

88
00:04:09,000 --> 00:04:10,708
Oh, a little bit more.

89
00:04:12,833 --> 00:04:14,333
Okay, he's done.

90
00:04:14,416 --> 00:04:16,791
Good boy! Good boy.

91
00:04:16,875 --> 00:04:17,875
Good boys.

92
00:04:17,916 --> 00:04:19,666
Very good boys. Both of you.

93
00:04:19,750 --> 00:04:21,541
- I hate you.
- You love me.

94
00:04:21,625 --> 00:04:23,500
Time to take this fella home.

95
00:04:23,583 --> 00:04:26,583
- [rock music playing]
- [indistinct chatter]

96
00:04:34,291 --> 00:04:36,291
[rock music and chatter continue]

97
00:04:43,458 --> 00:04:45,000
Puppy coming through!

98
00:04:46,166 --> 00:04:47,041
[woman 1] Puppy!

99
00:04:47,125 --> 00:04:48,250
I got the VIP.

100
00:04:48,333 --> 00:04:49,333
[woman 2] Oh, hi!

101
00:04:49,375 --> 00:04:51,458
- I know. I know. I know.
- [women laughing]

102
00:04:51,958 --> 00:04:53,166
[woman 3] Hi!

103
00:04:57,833 --> 00:04:59,083
You having fun, buddy?

104
00:05:00,250 --> 00:05:02,625
Oh. You know this is all for you, right?

105
00:05:03,125 --> 00:05:05,458
This is your homecoming.

106
00:05:05,541 --> 00:05:08,500
This party is fun.

107
00:05:09,000 --> 00:05:12,208
I cannot believe
that all these people showed up for...

108
00:05:13,541 --> 00:05:14,583
What is his name?

109
00:05:15,250 --> 00:05:16,250
I don't know.

110
00:05:17,041 --> 00:05:18,166
What is your name?

111
00:05:18,875 --> 00:05:20,541
[laughing]

112
00:05:20,625 --> 00:05:22,416
He gonked me on the head.

113
00:05:22,500 --> 00:05:24,375
- He did what?
- I mean... I mean bonked.

114
00:05:24,458 --> 00:05:26,250
[barks]

115
00:05:26,333 --> 00:05:27,791
- Wait, that's it.
- What is it?

116
00:05:29,708 --> 00:05:31,458
- "Gonker."
- [barks]

117
00:05:31,541 --> 00:05:34,416
- Hey, yeah, he likes it. Gonker.
- What is a gonker?

118
00:05:36,208 --> 00:05:37,416
He's a Gonker.

119
00:05:37,500 --> 00:05:41,083
Gonker! Gonker! Gonker!

120
00:05:41,166 --> 00:05:47,791
[all chanting] Gonker! Gonker! Gonker!
Gonker! Gonker! Gonker! Gonker!

121
00:05:47,875 --> 00:05:49,875
[lively music playing]

122
00:06:01,958 --> 00:06:03,666
We're gonna be late to class.

123
00:06:11,791 --> 00:06:13,416
[instructor] Take a deep breath,

124
00:06:13,958 --> 00:06:17,500
and we're gonna glide into downward dog.

125
00:06:18,750 --> 00:06:20,666
[uplifting music continues]

126
00:06:21,375 --> 00:06:22,375
Ready?

127
00:06:22,416 --> 00:06:23,416
Go. Go get it.

128
00:06:24,541 --> 00:06:25,791
No, come back. Come back.

129
00:06:26,958 --> 00:06:30,250
- Oh, go get it! Come on.
- [Gonker barks]

130
00:06:30,333 --> 00:06:31,916
[laughs] Go, come on.

131
00:06:32,000 --> 00:06:33,458
- Hey! Whoosh!
- [Gonker yips]

132
00:06:34,166 --> 00:06:36,166
[uplifting music continues]

133
00:06:44,958 --> 00:06:46,583
Yeah, there you go!

134
00:06:46,666 --> 00:06:48,708
There you go, buddy! Come here.

135
00:06:48,791 --> 00:06:50,791
[uplifting music continues]

136
00:07:02,375 --> 00:07:04,583
[Fielding] Yes! That's it, buddy!
Bring it back.

137
00:07:10,625 --> 00:07:13,958
Boosh! You guys see it?
What did I tell you? The boy is talented.

138
00:07:21,875 --> 00:07:23,515
I'm not opening a haunted house with you.

139
00:07:23,541 --> 00:07:25,666
[woman] Wait.
Did you guys hear about Lainey?

140
00:07:25,750 --> 00:07:28,750
- What?
- She got a job at Boeing. Six figures.

141
00:07:28,833 --> 00:07:30,166
- No, stop.
- [Fielding] Really?

142
00:07:30,250 --> 00:07:32,166
- [Nate] Wow.
- Six figures? Like, in money?

143
00:07:32,250 --> 00:07:34,625
- Yeah, and she gets to stay in Virginia.
- Stop.

144
00:07:35,208 --> 00:07:37,958
- I don't know anyone in St. Louis.
- What's in St. Louis?

145
00:07:38,500 --> 00:07:40,041
- My job.
- Yeah.

146
00:07:40,125 --> 00:07:41,916
I'm doing PR for Anheuser-Busch.

147
00:07:42,000 --> 00:07:44,059
- I start in, like, two weeks.
- You didn't know that?

148
00:07:44,083 --> 00:07:47,041
- You're working for a beer company?
- Dream job, right?

149
00:07:47,125 --> 00:07:50,250
Wait, hold on. Do... Do you all have jobs?

150
00:07:50,333 --> 00:07:52,333
Uh, yeah, bud, we do.

151
00:07:52,416 --> 00:07:55,541
Kinda. We just, uh, didn't...
didn't wanna say anything.

152
00:07:56,125 --> 00:07:57,875
Well, okay. Wait, hold on now.

153
00:07:57,958 --> 00:08:00,833
I'm... I'm not some loser
who can't get a job.

154
00:08:00,916 --> 00:08:03,916
I just...
I don't know what job I can do yet,

155
00:08:04,000 --> 00:08:06,625
so I gotta, like,
figure that out first, you know?

156
00:08:06,708 --> 00:08:09,958
Right. Isn't that kinda what
the last four years were for, though?

157
00:08:10,041 --> 00:08:11,166
Mmm...

158
00:08:15,166 --> 00:08:16,875
- That's my parents.
- Yes, it is.

159
00:08:16,958 --> 00:08:18,583
- Uh, hide the beers.
- [Nate] Good idea.

160
00:08:18,666 --> 00:08:20,750
- Uh, we're 21.
- It's 10:30 in the morning.

161
00:08:20,833 --> 00:08:21,833
Good point.

162
00:08:22,625 --> 00:08:24,791
[suspenseful music playing]

163
00:08:28,333 --> 00:08:29,708
- Fielding!
- Hey, Mom.

164
00:08:29,791 --> 00:08:31,000
Hi!

165
00:08:31,083 --> 00:08:33,083
- Fielding!
- Dad.

166
00:08:33,750 --> 00:08:36,250
What... What are you guys doing here?

167
00:08:36,333 --> 00:08:41,375
Well, I... I think my investment entitles
me to see you in a robe and a funny hat.

168
00:08:42,375 --> 00:08:43,708
Well, graduation's tomorrow.

169
00:08:43,791 --> 00:08:46,625
Yeah. We told you
that we were coming up the day before.

170
00:08:46,708 --> 00:08:50,333
Right. Sorry. I forgot about that.
I've, um, been busy.

171
00:08:50,416 --> 00:08:51,416
Oh.

172
00:08:53,125 --> 00:08:54,750
Yeah, I can see that.

173
00:08:56,791 --> 00:08:58,125
Well, we have a surprise for you.

174
00:08:58,208 --> 00:08:59,041
Oh.

175
00:08:59,125 --> 00:09:00,541
Oh, a surprise!

176
00:09:01,250 --> 00:09:04,375
Is that Peyton I see? Come here!
What? Oh, my God.

177
00:09:04,458 --> 00:09:05,958
W-What are you doing here?

178
00:09:06,041 --> 00:09:07,583
You know, I took my last exam early

179
00:09:07,666 --> 00:09:09,875
so I could fly out
and see my bro get his parchment.

180
00:09:09,958 --> 00:09:12,458
- Look at you. Best sister ever.
- You know. I try.

181
00:09:12,541 --> 00:09:13,750
- [Gonker barks]
- Oh!

182
00:09:13,833 --> 00:09:16,083
Whoa, Gonker! Sorry about that.

183
00:09:16,166 --> 00:09:17,583
- That's okay.
- Whoa, hey!

184
00:09:17,666 --> 00:09:19,309
- [Fielding] All right.
- Whose dog is this?

185
00:09:19,333 --> 00:09:20,333
[Fielding] He's...

186
00:09:23,375 --> 00:09:24,708
It's a bad idea.

187
00:09:24,791 --> 00:09:27,166
Okay, well, it's not an idea.
It's a reality.

188
00:09:27,250 --> 00:09:28,250
It's a mistake.

189
00:09:28,333 --> 00:09:31,166
He's not a mistake.
He's... He's my best friend.

190
00:09:31,250 --> 00:09:35,000
You can't even take care of yourself,
let alone another living being.

191
00:09:35,083 --> 00:09:37,291
Okay, I take care of Gonker just fine.

192
00:09:37,375 --> 00:09:39,458
So why's he drinking out of a beer bong?

193
00:09:42,000 --> 00:09:45,333
He's not. That's a chemistry thing.

194
00:09:45,416 --> 00:09:47,208
Come here, Gonker. Come on, buddy.

195
00:09:47,708 --> 00:09:48,791
Come on, let's go.

196
00:09:50,708 --> 00:09:54,708
- What kind of a name is "Gonker"?
- He gonked me in the head.

197
00:09:55,375 --> 00:09:57,125
I see you haven't recovered
from the trauma.

198
00:09:58,083 --> 00:10:01,416
Look, son, you're about to head out
into the real world.

199
00:10:01,500 --> 00:10:03,541
You're not gonna have any time
to spend with Gonker.

200
00:10:03,625 --> 00:10:05,625
What's he gonna do
when you're at work all day?

201
00:10:05,708 --> 00:10:06,708
"Work"?

202
00:10:07,208 --> 00:10:08,625
Dad, come on.

203
00:10:11,500 --> 00:10:12,958
Have you called Mr. Kobrenner?

204
00:10:13,958 --> 00:10:16,041
Accounting? I suck at math.

205
00:10:16,125 --> 00:10:17,666
Or Matt Price at Harper Lewis.

206
00:10:17,750 --> 00:10:21,416
Dad, I'm not equipped
to handle medical supplies sales.

207
00:10:21,500 --> 00:10:25,083
Then what are you gonna do
when, in 24 hours, this whole party ends?

208
00:10:25,166 --> 00:10:27,125
Other than be back at home
with Mom and Dad,

209
00:10:27,208 --> 00:10:29,208
exactly where you were four years ago.

210
00:10:32,166 --> 00:10:34,041
[tense music playing]

211
00:10:34,125 --> 00:10:36,458
- [Fielding] Come on, boy.
- [indistinct chatter]

212
00:10:41,875 --> 00:10:42,875
Hi.

213
00:10:44,041 --> 00:10:45,375
Uh, excuse me, sorry. Hey.

214
00:10:46,250 --> 00:10:48,291
Uh, come on. Excuse me, sorry. Sorry.

215
00:10:48,375 --> 00:10:50,500
Oh, Mom, Dad.

216
00:10:50,583 --> 00:10:51,750
[Fielding panting]

217
00:10:51,833 --> 00:10:53,000
[clears throat]

218
00:10:53,125 --> 00:10:54,541
I don't know what to say.

219
00:10:54,625 --> 00:10:55,458
Um...

220
00:10:55,541 --> 00:10:57,541
It's fine.
I'm sure there'll be another ceremony.

221
00:10:57,625 --> 00:10:59,041
Oh, wait. There's only one.

222
00:11:00,375 --> 00:11:01,750
Fielding, what happened?

223
00:11:01,833 --> 00:11:04,291
Well, I really took to heart
what Dad said yesterday

224
00:11:04,375 --> 00:11:07,041
about how I only
had 24 hours left here, so...

225
00:11:07,541 --> 00:11:10,791
Uh, Gonk and I slept out by the river
'cause he loves it there.

226
00:11:10,875 --> 00:11:13,166
We listened to frogs
and talked about the stars.

227
00:11:13,250 --> 00:11:15,125
- You talked?
- And we played flashlight chase.

228
00:11:15,208 --> 00:11:17,833
- He likes to chase a light on the ground.
- We can do the math.

229
00:11:17,916 --> 00:11:18,833
Right.

230
00:11:18,916 --> 00:11:22,958
And we must have fallen asleep
pretty late, 'cause, um, I overslept.

231
00:11:23,958 --> 00:11:26,750
Well, I'm sure it's worth
the six-hour round trip

232
00:11:26,833 --> 00:11:29,583
just to see 4,000 strangers
all dressed in the same outfit.

233
00:11:29,666 --> 00:11:33,666
It's okay. We can still go out
for a celebratory meal, right?

234
00:11:34,333 --> 00:11:36,291
Actually, Mom, I, um...

235
00:11:36,791 --> 00:11:39,625
My stomach's been feeling a little off
the past few days.

236
00:11:40,583 --> 00:11:42,250
Uh, maybe we can rain check?

237
00:11:44,375 --> 00:11:45,375
Sure.

238
00:11:45,458 --> 00:11:49,125
Yeah, we'll have plenty of time
for family meals back home.

239
00:11:49,208 --> 00:11:50,791
It's all right. I, uh...

240
00:11:50,875 --> 00:11:53,125
It's okay. Accidents happen.

241
00:11:53,791 --> 00:11:55,000
I'm really proud of you.

242
00:11:55,083 --> 00:11:56,708
- And I love you.
- I love you too.

243
00:11:56,791 --> 00:11:59,625
Well, congratulations on graduating.

244
00:12:00,708 --> 00:12:01,541
Drive safe.

245
00:12:01,625 --> 00:12:04,000
Thanks. And, again, I'm so sorry.

246
00:12:05,791 --> 00:12:06,791
Um...

247
00:12:07,208 --> 00:12:08,416
I'll see you tomorrow.

248
00:12:08,500 --> 00:12:11,833
Um, no, I'm going back to Seattle tonight.

249
00:12:11,916 --> 00:12:12,916
What?

250
00:12:13,625 --> 00:12:16,125
Wait, just you, you...
You cannot leave me alone with them.

251
00:12:16,208 --> 00:12:18,328
I got a summer job
in the Creative Writing department.

252
00:12:19,416 --> 00:12:21,791
Look, you say
you don't wanna live with the 'rents,

253
00:12:21,875 --> 00:12:23,958
then why don't you get a job
and go pay rent?

254
00:12:24,458 --> 00:12:27,208
Besides, you won't be alone, right?
You got Gonker.

255
00:12:30,375 --> 00:12:33,000
Uh, he wants you to rub his belly.

256
00:12:33,083 --> 00:12:36,833
- ["Let Down" by Michigander playing]
<i>- ♪ You're a concept worth exploring ♪</i>

257
00:12:36,916 --> 00:12:39,416
<i>- ♪ Never nervous, never boring... ♪</i>
- [whimpers]

258
00:12:39,500 --> 00:12:43,250
- All right, Mr. Big Adult Professor Man.
- You could do it too.

259
00:12:43,833 --> 00:12:46,041
Yeah, grad school? For what?

260
00:12:47,500 --> 00:12:48,500
Good point.

261
00:12:49,708 --> 00:12:52,125
I'm gonna miss you too, buddy.
All right? Now, listen.

262
00:12:52,208 --> 00:12:55,708
Don't let the suburbs tame you, all right?
You're a wild beast.

263
00:12:55,791 --> 00:12:57,541
- [barks]
- [Nate] Don't forget it.

264
00:13:00,000 --> 00:13:03,333
How lucky am I to have something
that makes saying goodbye so hard?

265
00:13:04,416 --> 00:13:05,250
Oh, Gandhi.

266
00:13:05,333 --> 00:13:07,291
Winnie the Pooh, man. Come here.

267
00:13:07,375 --> 00:13:10,083
- ["Let Down" continues playing]
<i>- ♪ I got high hopes ♪</i>

268
00:13:10,166 --> 00:13:11,333
Take care, all right?

269
00:13:12,750 --> 00:13:14,166
- Dude, do the...
- No.

270
00:13:14,250 --> 00:13:15,333
- No?
- I'll work on it.

271
00:13:15,416 --> 00:13:17,041
I still wanna do the bird thing.

272
00:13:19,041 --> 00:13:21,541
- Next time. See ya.
- Later, buddy.

273
00:13:21,625 --> 00:13:25,125
<i>♪ Even though I've only met you ♪</i>

274
00:13:25,208 --> 00:13:27,916
<i>♪ I don't wanna mess it up ♪</i>

275
00:13:28,750 --> 00:13:31,250
<i>♪ I'm probably gonna mess it up ♪</i>

276
00:13:32,875 --> 00:13:36,875
<i>♪ Yeah, you're walking down the stairs
On a Wednesday night ♪</i>

277
00:13:36,958 --> 00:13:40,166
<i>♪ Sure, it's kinda cold
But I feel all right ♪</i>

278
00:13:40,250 --> 00:13:43,208
<i>♪ 'Cause I got you in the front seat ♪</i>

279
00:13:44,000 --> 00:13:46,916
<i>♪ And you keep on lookin' at me ♪</i>

280
00:13:47,708 --> 00:13:50,125
<i>♪ 'Cause I got high hopes... ♪</i>

281
00:13:50,208 --> 00:13:52,625
It's okay, boy. We'll figure it out.

282
00:13:52,708 --> 00:13:54,375
<i>♪ High hopes ♪</i>

283
00:13:54,458 --> 00:13:57,166
<i>♪ But they let me down ♪</i>

284
00:13:58,041 --> 00:14:01,125
<i>♪ They usually let me down ♪</i>

285
00:14:02,166 --> 00:14:06,041
<i>♪ Yeah, I got high hopes ♪</i>

286
00:14:06,125 --> 00:14:09,000
<i>♪ I got high hopes ♪</i>

287
00:14:09,083 --> 00:14:12,291
<i>♪ But they let me down ♪</i>

288
00:14:12,375 --> 00:14:16,375
<i>- ♪ Oh, they usually let me down ♪</i>
- [song fading]

289
00:14:19,125 --> 00:14:20,208
This is it.

290
00:14:22,041 --> 00:14:24,625
Hey, there's gonna be
an adjustment period,

291
00:14:24,708 --> 00:14:25,541
so let's just...

292
00:14:25,625 --> 00:14:28,166
Hey, let's just play it cool, all right?

293
00:14:29,666 --> 00:14:31,041
- [Gonker barks]
- We're home.

294
00:14:31,125 --> 00:14:34,083
[Ginny] Aw, the graduates are back!

295
00:14:34,583 --> 00:14:35,666
Hi! Oh!

296
00:14:35,750 --> 00:14:38,416
[Fielding] Oh, Gonk, down!
Hey, down, boy. Hey.

297
00:14:38,500 --> 00:14:40,375
- He wants to kiss you.
- That's so nice.

298
00:14:40,458 --> 00:14:41,875
Here you go, sport.

299
00:14:41,958 --> 00:14:43,291
Uh, what's this?

300
00:14:43,375 --> 00:14:44,375
Shock collar.

301
00:14:44,750 --> 00:14:47,125
Oh, no, he's... He's not wearing this.

302
00:14:48,041 --> 00:14:51,416
- Mom, he's a wild beast.
- He's a domesticated animal.

303
00:14:51,500 --> 00:14:53,541
Let's not go that far.
You saw the frat house.

304
00:14:53,625 --> 00:14:57,583
No, I'm serious. He's used to being free.
He ran around campus all the time.

305
00:14:57,666 --> 00:14:59,750
We're not on campus anymore.
We're in civilization.

306
00:15:00,500 --> 00:15:03,958
And in civilization, people keep
their refrigerators in their kitchen

307
00:15:04,041 --> 00:15:05,333
and their dogs in the yard.

308
00:15:05,416 --> 00:15:06,416
No, I...

309
00:15:07,083 --> 00:15:11,166
So we have some sensors
set up outside right by the woods,

310
00:15:11,250 --> 00:15:13,791
so he can get close, but not too close.

311
00:15:13,875 --> 00:15:16,791
And if he does, he gets a little zap.

312
00:15:16,875 --> 00:15:18,875
Not enough to hurt him,
just enough to teach him.

313
00:15:19,375 --> 00:15:22,095
- It's gonna break his spirit.
- It goes on his neck, not his spirit.

314
00:15:23,125 --> 00:15:24,208
[barks]

315
00:15:26,583 --> 00:15:31,750
[Gonker barks]

316
00:15:31,833 --> 00:15:34,083
[Ginny] What are... What is it, buddy?

317
00:15:34,166 --> 00:15:36,166
[barking continues]

318
00:15:36,791 --> 00:15:38,541
[Fielding] No, no, no! Gonker!

319
00:15:39,083 --> 00:15:41,625
- Hey! Hey! Gonker! Gonker, come on, man!
- [Ginny] Oh!

320
00:15:41,708 --> 00:15:44,208
- Don't worry, the collar will stop him.
- [Ginny] Gonker!

321
00:15:44,291 --> 00:15:46,000
[Fielding] Gonker! Hey! Hey!

322
00:15:46,083 --> 00:15:47,375
- [Ginny] No!
- [John] Gonker!

323
00:15:47,458 --> 00:15:49,218
- [Ginny] He's getting away!
- [Fielding] No!

324
00:15:49,291 --> 00:15:50,771
- [collar zapping]
- [Gonker whimpers]

325
00:15:50,833 --> 00:15:53,041
- [collar beeping]
- Oh, what?

326
00:15:56,333 --> 00:16:00,416
Oh, yeah, Gonk! Fight the power!
You go get that fox!

327
00:16:02,500 --> 00:16:04,250
They told me it would stop any dog.

328
00:16:05,250 --> 00:16:07,208
Well, Gonker isn't any dog.

329
00:16:07,291 --> 00:16:09,208
What if he gets lost?

330
00:16:09,291 --> 00:16:12,375
No, Mom, he'd run around campus for hours.
He always came back.

331
00:16:12,458 --> 00:16:16,166
- But he doesn't know his way around here.
- He'll be fine. I promise.

332
00:16:17,125 --> 00:16:19,291
[voice fading]
No, he's a really, really special dog.

333
00:16:21,916 --> 00:16:24,625
A bit of Japan that I can leave behind.

334
00:16:26,875 --> 00:16:29,333
For your family's hospitality
during our visit.

335
00:16:29,416 --> 00:16:31,000
- [gasps]
- [man] He's yours now.

336
00:16:32,333 --> 00:16:33,333
His name is Oji.

337
00:16:34,041 --> 00:16:35,208
I love him.

338
00:16:37,416 --> 00:16:38,458
Can I play with him?

339
00:16:39,916 --> 00:16:41,416
Fifty meters in either direction.

340
00:16:41,500 --> 00:16:44,416
We need to go to town soon.
I don't want to have to look for you.

341
00:16:45,166 --> 00:16:46,166
Come on, Oji.

342
00:16:49,666 --> 00:16:50,958
[Oji yips]

343
00:16:51,625 --> 00:16:52,625
Come on, boy.

344
00:16:55,875 --> 00:16:59,083
- Want some food?
- Uh, no, I'm fine, but I could use a nap.

345
00:17:03,166 --> 00:17:04,833
[indistinct rhythmic grunting]

346
00:17:06,875 --> 00:17:08,083
- What?
- Oh, God.

347
00:17:08,708 --> 00:17:10,708
[grunting continues]

348
00:17:12,375 --> 00:17:14,375
[grunting continues]

349
00:17:17,125 --> 00:17:18,125
Son?

350
00:17:20,375 --> 00:17:21,375
Son!

351
00:17:22,208 --> 00:17:25,666
- Oh, hey. I'm sorry. Did I wake you?
- I think you woke your Aunt Jenny.

352
00:17:25,750 --> 00:17:27,851
- She's been dead for nine years.
- What are you doing?

353
00:17:27,875 --> 00:17:30,083
Oh, it's a breathing technique.

354
00:17:30,166 --> 00:17:32,166
A modified Agni Prasana<i>. </i>It's...

355
00:17:32,250 --> 00:17:36,083
We time it to the end of our sleep cycle.
Keeps me centered, stabilizes my gut.

356
00:17:36,750 --> 00:17:37,583
What's his deal?

357
00:17:37,666 --> 00:17:38,666
Uh...

358
00:17:39,250 --> 00:17:43,583
Oh, he likes to do it with me.
Or maybe he just wants a belly rub?

359
00:17:43,666 --> 00:17:45,000
Don't look at me, pal.

360
00:17:46,750 --> 00:17:47,750
Okay, bye.

361
00:17:49,750 --> 00:17:53,166
[John] So our assessment is that
any positive movement in the next quarter

362
00:17:53,250 --> 00:17:54,375
is gonna be unlikely.

363
00:17:54,458 --> 00:17:57,017
[woman on video] <i>So you're holding off
on investments until when?</i>

364
00:17:57,041 --> 00:18:00,041
No. My team's telling me
you should keep your powder dry,

365
00:18:00,125 --> 00:18:02,875
at least until the local elections
or maybe after the rainy season.

366
00:18:02,958 --> 00:18:05,875
[woman] <i>Implementing a program is
gonna be possible at some point, right?</i>

367
00:18:05,958 --> 00:18:07,333
Can you excuse me for one second?

368
00:18:07,416 --> 00:18:08,791
- I'm so sorry.
- [woman] <i>Uh, sure.</i>

369
00:18:09,625 --> 00:18:10,625
[shouts] Fielding!

370
00:18:14,000 --> 00:18:14,833
Yes, sir?

371
00:18:14,916 --> 00:18:18,291
I'm on a Zoom call with five people.
He's just sitting here whining.

372
00:18:18,916 --> 00:18:20,041
He wants to play fetch.

373
00:18:22,000 --> 00:18:23,000
All right.

374
00:18:27,791 --> 00:18:28,791
Go get it.

375
00:18:32,125 --> 00:18:33,750
He needs to choose the stick.

376
00:18:34,750 --> 00:18:35,666
He needs to choose it?

377
00:18:35,750 --> 00:18:37,666
- Yeah, it changes every day.
- [Gonker whining]

378
00:18:41,666 --> 00:18:42,666
Now what?

379
00:18:44,125 --> 00:18:45,750
He wants you to watch him choose.

380
00:18:46,833 --> 00:18:48,416
It's no fun if you don't watch.

381
00:18:51,541 --> 00:18:52,625
Hey.

382
00:18:54,041 --> 00:18:55,041
I'm watching.

383
00:18:57,458 --> 00:19:00,458
["I'll Be Your Best Friend"
by Bamtone playing]

384
00:19:01,625 --> 00:19:02,958
- [barks]
- Oh!

385
00:19:03,916 --> 00:19:06,666
You have your bed and I have my bed.

386
00:19:06,750 --> 00:19:09,625
And... this is my bed!

387
00:19:11,125 --> 00:19:16,208
<i>♪ With a great big smile
As big as the big blue ocean tide ♪</i>

388
00:19:16,916 --> 00:19:19,000
<i>♪ La, la, la, la, la, la... ♪</i>

389
00:19:19,083 --> 00:19:20,791
They choose popes quicker.

390
00:19:21,833 --> 00:19:26,250
<i>♪ If you call, I'll be right up... ♪</i>

391
00:19:26,333 --> 00:19:28,583
[frustrated] I give up!

392
00:19:29,250 --> 00:19:32,208
- I give up.
<i>- ♪ If you fall, I'll pick you up ♪</i>

393
00:19:32,291 --> 00:19:34,750
- [indistinct rhythmic grunting]
- [Ginny groans]

394
00:19:34,833 --> 00:19:37,791
[grunting continues]

395
00:19:38,458 --> 00:19:41,083
When you're done,
please smother me to death as well.

396
00:19:41,875 --> 00:19:43,125
[Gonker whining]

397
00:19:43,208 --> 00:19:45,083
<i>♪ Ever since I met you ♪</i>

398
00:19:45,166 --> 00:19:49,333
<i>♪ I've been floating
Like a bird across the sky ♪</i>

399
00:19:49,416 --> 00:19:53,583
<i>♪ Let the wind be our
Guide to all these dreams</i>...<i> ♪</i>

400
00:19:53,666 --> 00:19:55,750
[Ginny] Oh, you like birds too, huh?

401
00:19:56,666 --> 00:19:58,250
You're not a wild beast.

402
00:19:59,541 --> 00:20:01,041
You're a sweetheart, aren't you?

403
00:20:01,125 --> 00:20:05,250
<i>♪ If you call, I'll be right up ♪</i>

404
00:20:05,750 --> 00:20:06,750
[John] Oh!

405
00:20:06,833 --> 00:20:09,041
You're certain about this? All right.

406
00:20:10,250 --> 00:20:11,250
Go get it!

407
00:20:11,333 --> 00:20:13,875
["I'll Be Your Best Friend"
continues playing]

408
00:20:24,750 --> 00:20:26,875
<i>- ♪ I'll be your best friend ♪</i>
- [song finishes]

409
00:20:26,958 --> 00:20:28,458
Yes! That's it, boy!

410
00:20:28,541 --> 00:20:31,541
- [exclaims] That was actually kinda cool.
- Hooray!

411
00:20:31,625 --> 00:20:33,125
[Fielding] Wait. Did you see that?

412
00:20:33,208 --> 00:20:34,666
- [Ginny] Yes!
- Yes!

413
00:20:34,750 --> 00:20:35,958
Yeah, that's a good boy!

414
00:20:36,041 --> 00:20:37,916
- That was impressive!
- That's a talented boy!

415
00:20:38,000 --> 00:20:40,000
[thunder rumbling]

416
00:20:48,791 --> 00:20:49,791
Gonker?

417
00:20:51,708 --> 00:20:53,416
Worst-named dog in the world.

418
00:20:54,250 --> 00:20:56,458
- [exhales]
- [Gonker whimpers]

419
00:20:56,541 --> 00:20:58,833
- [thunder continues]
- Gonker?

420
00:20:59,458 --> 00:21:01,458
[Gonker whimpering]

421
00:21:06,750 --> 00:21:07,875
What are you doing?

422
00:21:09,458 --> 00:21:10,458
Hmm?

423
00:21:11,083 --> 00:21:12,541
- [whimpering]
- Oh.

424
00:21:12,625 --> 00:21:14,750
You're scared
of the thunder and lightning.

425
00:21:16,333 --> 00:21:17,916
Aren't you? Yeah.

426
00:21:19,208 --> 00:21:21,125
Just like Fielding when he was little.

427
00:21:23,666 --> 00:21:26,416
You know, I used to have
to sing to him to make him feel better.

428
00:21:33,166 --> 00:21:35,791
<i>♪ Like a rhinestone cowboy ♪</i>

429
00:21:38,000 --> 00:21:39,791
<i>♪ Riding out on a horse ♪</i>

430
00:21:40,541 --> 00:21:43,166
<i>♪ In a star-spangled rodeo ♪</i>

431
00:21:47,375 --> 00:21:49,833
<i>♪ Rhinestone cowboy ♪</i>

432
00:21:51,500 --> 00:21:56,500
<i>♪ Gettin' cards and letters
From people I don't even know ♪</i>

433
00:21:57,250 --> 00:21:58,500
[rain pattering]

434
00:21:58,583 --> 00:22:01,250
<i>♪ And offers comin' over the phone ♪</i>

435
00:22:06,083 --> 00:22:07,083
Yeah.

436
00:22:10,708 --> 00:22:12,333
[Ginny] I'm home!

437
00:22:12,416 --> 00:22:15,291
I got blueberry pie
from the farmers market

438
00:22:15,375 --> 00:22:17,416
for when the Connors come.

439
00:22:17,500 --> 00:22:21,125
And I got banana cream for us
'cause we deserve it.

440
00:22:22,333 --> 00:22:25,000
What, no greeting?

441
00:22:27,541 --> 00:22:31,208
You all tuckered out
from fetch and foxes and things...

442
00:22:32,500 --> 00:22:34,916
[clicks tongue] Oh, shoot.

443
00:22:37,500 --> 00:22:38,916
[sighs] All right.

444
00:22:39,666 --> 00:22:42,333
I'll get the big pieces,
and you come get the rest.

445
00:22:47,916 --> 00:22:50,500
Hey, Fielding. Come here for a sec.

446
00:22:50,583 --> 00:22:52,750
Uh-oh! [laughs]

447
00:22:52,833 --> 00:22:54,208
You want me to get the mop?

448
00:22:54,708 --> 00:22:57,291
No, it's Gonker.
He didn't greet me when I came in.

449
00:22:57,375 --> 00:22:59,833
And now there's food on the floor
and he's not touching it?

450
00:23:02,000 --> 00:23:03,291
He didn't eat his breakfast?

451
00:23:05,583 --> 00:23:08,291
I think that's his dinner from last night.

452
00:23:11,416 --> 00:23:13,583
[Fielding] Hey, boy,
you wanna go for a run?

453
00:23:15,958 --> 00:23:18,125
No? Hey, come on! Come on, let's go play!

454
00:23:23,208 --> 00:23:24,416
[whines softly]

455
00:23:24,916 --> 00:23:26,833
- Mom?
- I'll call the vet.

456
00:23:29,083 --> 00:23:30,916
Hey. It's okay.

457
00:23:31,000 --> 00:23:32,875
[somber music playing]

458
00:23:38,833 --> 00:23:42,125
[somber music continues]

459
00:24:12,583 --> 00:24:16,625
Addison's disease is when the body
fails to produce enough glucocorticoids.

460
00:24:16,708 --> 00:24:21,166
You fall into adrenal insufficiency,
which causes pain, low blood pressure.

461
00:24:21,250 --> 00:24:22,833
You can lapse into a coma.

462
00:24:22,916 --> 00:24:24,583
Wait. He's in a coma?

463
00:24:24,666 --> 00:24:26,166
Oh, no, he's sedated.

464
00:24:26,666 --> 00:24:30,000
Now, with medication,
Addison's can be controlled,

465
00:24:30,083 --> 00:24:33,625
but Gonker's condition
had laid dormant his entire life.

466
00:24:34,125 --> 00:24:38,291
And he's had an acute episode.
He's not out of the woods yet.

467
00:24:38,375 --> 00:24:41,541
And if he survives,
he's going to need a shot every 30 days.

468
00:24:41,625 --> 00:24:43,166
If he survives?

469
00:24:43,250 --> 00:24:46,416
I'm sorry, but it's 50/50
he makes it through the night.

470
00:24:49,291 --> 00:24:50,208
[Fielding] Um...

471
00:24:50,291 --> 00:24:51,708
Then I'm gonna stay with him.

472
00:24:51,791 --> 00:24:54,916
[vet] Not a good idea. He's gonna lapse
in and out of consciousness.

473
00:24:55,000 --> 00:24:58,166
And if he sees you,
it'll rile him up, and he needs sleep.

474
00:24:58,666 --> 00:25:00,500
Best thing for both of you is rest.

475
00:25:01,000 --> 00:25:03,500
My staff and I will be with him
around the clock.

476
00:25:05,500 --> 00:25:06,500
I promise.

477
00:25:17,458 --> 00:25:21,333
Here. Now Gonker can have
some nice clean bowls when he gets back.

478
00:25:22,000 --> 00:25:23,625
[Fielding] Yeah, if he gets back.

479
00:25:24,458 --> 00:25:25,458
Don't talk like that.

480
00:25:25,500 --> 00:25:28,208
Well, they said online
it's worse the longer it goes untreated.

481
00:25:29,000 --> 00:25:31,916
He spent the whole first year of his life
with no medication, nothing.

482
00:25:32,000 --> 00:25:35,416
In college, did you ever notice him
getting worn out or anything?

483
00:25:35,500 --> 00:25:36,916
Well, some days,

484
00:25:37,000 --> 00:25:41,166
but I thought he was tired from,
you know, playing fetch or hiking.

