00:38:26,166 --> 00:38:29,166
Oh, I'm sorry.
I would hate for me to embarrass you.

730
00:38:29,250 --> 00:38:31,583
- At least you admit it.
- Admit what?

731
00:38:31,666 --> 00:38:34,125
- That you're embarrassed of me.
- Don't be ridiculous.

732
00:38:34,625 --> 00:38:36,458
Am I being ridiculous?

733
00:38:38,208 --> 00:38:41,500
Because what's the opposite
of embarrassment? It's pride.

734
00:38:41,583 --> 00:38:44,916
So, can you say you're proud
of how I live my life?

735
00:38:45,875 --> 00:38:49,125
You know, from my ripped jeans
to my choices and everything in between.

736
00:38:49,208 --> 00:38:52,958
Well, Fielding, obviously,
there are decisions that you've made,

737
00:38:53,041 --> 00:38:54,666
how you spent your time in college,

738
00:38:54,750 --> 00:38:57,875
how you're spending your time now,
that I don't... I don't agree with.

739
00:38:57,958 --> 00:39:02,000
- And, frankly, I don't understand them...
- I guess we're just two different people.

740
00:39:02,083 --> 00:39:04,791
- Let me finish what I'm saying.
- There's no point, you know?

741
00:39:04,875 --> 00:39:07,958
'Cause I know that you think
that I'm irresponsible, and immature,

742
00:39:08,041 --> 00:39:10,166
and, you know,
Gonker's gonna die 'cause of me.

743
00:39:10,250 --> 00:39:11,958
- Fielding.
- There's hikers coming.

744
00:39:15,291 --> 00:39:17,291
Um, hi! Excuse me.

745
00:39:17,833 --> 00:39:20,625
I'm looking for my dog.
Just wondering if you've seen him.

746
00:39:20,708 --> 00:39:23,125
Or maybe you can help
spread the word if not.

747
00:39:23,208 --> 00:39:24,666
Yes, hi. This is Ginny Marshall.

748
00:39:24,750 --> 00:39:28,666
I just emailed you a note with a flyer
explaining my family's situation and...

749
00:39:29,166 --> 00:39:31,125
That's call waiting. I'll try you back.

750
00:39:31,833 --> 00:39:33,208
- John?
- Ms. Marshall.

751
00:39:33,708 --> 00:39:35,833
This is Kyle Gans at the <i>Virginia Sun.</i>

752
00:39:36,333 --> 00:39:37,333
I got your email.

753
00:39:37,416 --> 00:39:40,666
Oh! Thank you for calling back
so quickly, Mr. Gans. Yes.

754
00:39:40,750 --> 00:39:41,625
Um...

755
00:39:41,708 --> 00:39:45,875
I was wondering if we could put
a, um, a lost dog ad in your paper.

756
00:39:45,958 --> 00:39:48,416
<i>I'd be happy to reimburse you
for any expenses.</i>

757
00:39:48,500 --> 00:39:51,208
Actually,
I'm thinking of something bigger.

758
00:39:52,083 --> 00:39:53,666
I was struck by what you wrote.

759
00:39:54,750 --> 00:39:57,000
It was deeply personal.

760
00:39:57,625 --> 00:39:59,500
You're clearly heartbroken over your dog.

761
00:39:59,583 --> 00:40:03,875
Oh, well, yeah, I...
I did write the note, but, actually,

762
00:40:03,958 --> 00:40:05,750
<i>Gonker belongs to my son.</i>

763
00:40:07,041 --> 00:40:08,041
Really?

764
00:40:08,916 --> 00:40:10,791
Because it reads like you lost your dog.

765
00:40:14,291 --> 00:40:15,833
<i>Anyway, with your permission,</i>

766
00:40:16,625 --> 00:40:18,750
I'd like to write an article
about your search.

767
00:40:19,333 --> 00:40:20,333
[whispers] What?

768
00:40:21,541 --> 00:40:22,541
[gasps]

769
00:40:23,375 --> 00:40:24,655
[Ginny] <i>We're getting publicity.</i>

770
00:40:24,708 --> 00:40:28,125
<i>- The newspaper's gonna run an article.</i>
- An article? Really?

771
00:40:28,208 --> 00:40:30,583
With a photo of Gonker and everything.

772
00:40:30,666 --> 00:40:33,291
The Connor boys are here,
they're setting up a scanner for me,

773
00:40:33,375 --> 00:40:36,017
'cause the newspaper said
we need a certain resolution or something.

774
00:40:36,041 --> 00:40:38,458
I don't know. I called Janie
and she sent 'em right over.

775
00:40:38,541 --> 00:40:40,333
Great. Make sure you give 'em both a 20.

776
00:40:40,416 --> 00:40:42,750
[Ginny] Yeah, I already tried.
They refused.

777
00:40:42,833 --> 00:40:43,875
Isn't this wonderful?

778
00:40:43,958 --> 00:40:47,083
The <i>Virginia Sun </i>has a circulation
of, like, 6,000.

779
00:40:47,166 --> 00:40:49,083
I mean, Gonker has been
retweeted double that.

780
00:40:49,166 --> 00:40:50,500
We still haven't heard anything.

781
00:40:50,583 --> 00:40:53,166
Well, every little bit counts, right?

782
00:40:53,250 --> 00:40:54,875
All right. Well, keep up the good work.

783
00:40:54,958 --> 00:40:57,333
<i>We love you. We'll call you
from the road in the morning.</i>

784
00:40:57,833 --> 00:40:59,375
[Ginny] Okay. Love you too.

785
00:41:00,708 --> 00:41:02,458
[thunder rumbling]

786
00:41:16,166 --> 00:41:17,875
[thunder booming]

787
00:41:23,333 --> 00:41:25,458
- [thunder cracking]
- [Gonker whines]

788
00:41:27,375 --> 00:41:29,375
- [rain falling]
- [whining]

789
00:41:36,208 --> 00:41:38,125
[John muffled] We did 14 miles today.

790
00:41:40,125 --> 00:41:42,085
[clears throat]
I need you to keep up your energy.

791
00:41:42,125 --> 00:41:44,875
- I know you're upset, but...
- I'm not upset, Dad.

792
00:41:45,500 --> 00:41:46,500
It's...

793
00:41:47,500 --> 00:41:48,500
[John] It's what?

794
00:41:54,583 --> 00:41:55,625
All my friends,

795
00:41:56,708 --> 00:41:59,375
okay, they've all gone
and started their lives, and

796
00:42:00,166 --> 00:42:01,291
I'm happy for them.

797
00:42:03,041 --> 00:42:05,041
But it's like they pity me.

798
00:42:06,208 --> 00:42:09,208
I totally feel it. And you and Mom,
you guys judge me too.

799
00:42:09,791 --> 00:42:13,041
- Fielding, your mom and I don't judge you.
- Dad, yes, you do. Every day.

800
00:42:13,125 --> 00:42:14,250
In how you look at me.

801
00:42:15,875 --> 00:42:18,875
How you talk about me
when you think I can't hear you.

802
00:42:18,958 --> 00:42:20,708
[thunder continues in background]

803
00:42:20,791 --> 00:42:24,541
And when all of your friends, and your
mom, and your dad, and their friends,

804
00:42:24,625 --> 00:42:27,708
when everyone
looks at you like you're a loser, it's...

805
00:42:27,791 --> 00:42:29,750
[laughs] It's nice to have

806
00:42:29,833 --> 00:42:32,958
one soul on earth who thinks
you're fine just the way you are.

807
00:42:34,375 --> 00:42:36,000
Even if you are a little bit different

808
00:42:36,083 --> 00:42:38,958
or don't have a job,
or direction, or momentum.

809
00:42:40,125 --> 00:42:43,500
Just one soul who loves you because...

810
00:42:44,416 --> 00:42:45,416
Because you are you.

811
00:42:47,750 --> 00:42:49,666
That's who Gonker was for me, Dad.

812
00:42:51,833 --> 00:42:54,541
[voice breaking] Gonker was the only one
on the entire planet who...

813
00:42:55,041 --> 00:42:57,291
Who liked me just the way I am.

814
00:43:02,166 --> 00:43:05,750
Son, you're worried about Gonker
because you love him and he's lost.

815
00:43:07,875 --> 00:43:09,625
That's why I worry about you.

816
00:43:10,458 --> 00:43:11,583
You just did it again.

817
00:43:15,791 --> 00:43:19,416
Just because I'm trying to find my way
or whatever doesn't mean I'm lost.

818
00:43:20,791 --> 00:43:23,458
[somber music playing]

819
00:43:29,958 --> 00:43:32,958
- [somber music continues]
- [thunder rumbling]

820
00:43:37,916 --> 00:43:39,166
[car honks]

821
00:43:39,250 --> 00:43:42,458
Excuse me! Excuse me! Hi.

822
00:43:42,541 --> 00:43:43,375
Hi.

823
00:43:43,458 --> 00:43:46,791
Hi, um, were you handing these out
in the Hardee's earlier?

824
00:43:46,875 --> 00:43:48,541
Yeah. Have you seen him?

825
00:43:49,375 --> 00:43:51,208
Uh, no, sweetie, I haven't,

826
00:43:51,291 --> 00:43:54,000
but when my Tucker ran off
a few years ago,

827
00:43:54,083 --> 00:43:57,750
we went around with his brother Butchie,
and Tucker picked up his scent real fast.

828
00:43:57,833 --> 00:44:00,625
Some folks think dogs will pick up
the scent of another canine

829
00:44:00,708 --> 00:44:02,625
before they will a human scent.

830
00:44:02,708 --> 00:44:06,000
It's kinda left over
from when they needed to find their packs.

831
00:44:06,083 --> 00:44:07,916
I thought maybe it could help.

832
00:44:08,541 --> 00:44:09,750
Thank you.

833
00:44:15,916 --> 00:44:17,916
[majestic music playing]

834
00:44:27,250 --> 00:44:30,500
- Hey, we really appreciate this.
- Ah, you kiddin'?

835
00:44:30,583 --> 00:44:35,791
Yuri loves Gonker, and vice versa.
No doubt old Gonk will know his scent.

836
00:44:35,875 --> 00:44:38,041
I promise he'll never be off leash,

837
00:44:38,125 --> 00:44:40,875
and we'll feed him well,
get plenty of exercise.

838
00:44:40,958 --> 00:44:42,583
[Mr. Platt] Fresh air will do him good.

839
00:44:42,666 --> 00:44:45,708
Need him back a week from today.
Heading to Florida till the spring.

840
00:44:45,791 --> 00:44:48,083
You got it.
Hopefully, we'll be back with two dogs.

841
00:44:48,166 --> 00:44:52,125
[chuckles] All right. You be good, Yuri.
Help the Marshalls find their boy.

842
00:44:52,833 --> 00:44:55,375
[dramatic music playing]

843
00:45:00,625 --> 00:45:01,625
[Fielding] Gonk!

844
00:45:02,541 --> 00:45:03,541
Gonker!

845
00:45:06,541 --> 00:45:07,583
Gonker!

846
00:45:08,833 --> 00:45:10,375
[John on megaphone] Gonker!

847
00:45:13,333 --> 00:45:14,333
Gonk!

848
00:45:14,875 --> 00:45:16,875
- [John] Hey, excuse me.
- [hiker] Hey, how are ya?

849
00:45:16,958 --> 00:45:19,583
[John] We're looking for our dog.
Maybe you can help us.

850
00:45:19,666 --> 00:45:21,906
- Seen anything around here?
- No, haven't seen anything.

851
00:45:22,333 --> 00:45:24,053
- [Fielding] Thank you so much.
- Good luck.

852
00:45:25,250 --> 00:45:28,291
- [dramatic music continues]
- [John on megaphone] Gonker!

853
00:45:30,208 --> 00:45:32,666
Gonker!

854
00:45:34,875 --> 00:45:36,750
Gonker!

855
00:45:38,375 --> 00:45:39,875
Gonker!

856
00:45:39,958 --> 00:45:40,958
[Fielding] Gonker!

857
00:45:42,291 --> 00:45:44,833
[John on megaphone] Gonker!

858
00:45:44,916 --> 00:45:46,166
[woman] I'd love to help.

859
00:45:46,250 --> 00:45:49,041
I have a friend at the high school,
lets me make copies for free.

860
00:45:49,125 --> 00:45:51,208
I can put one up at the church,
the market.

861
00:45:51,791 --> 00:45:53,791
Oh, and the quarry
employs a whole lot of folk.

862
00:45:53,875 --> 00:45:56,666
I'll make sure they find one
on their windshield after work.

863
00:45:56,750 --> 00:46:00,291
- Thank you. You're a godsend.
- Tell my ex that. Good luck.

864
00:46:00,375 --> 00:46:02,416
- [motorbike revs]
- What about those guys?

865
00:46:03,666 --> 00:46:06,666
- [Fielding] Are you sure?
- Talk about covering a lot of ground.

866
00:46:07,625 --> 00:46:10,583
Right. They're on motorcycles.
They can't ride the trail.

867
00:46:10,666 --> 00:46:12,626
We don't know
if Gonker's gonna stay on the trail.

868
00:46:12,708 --> 00:46:14,166
- He could head into a city.
- Okay.

869
00:46:14,250 --> 00:46:16,208
But they just don't
look like the type of people

870
00:46:16,291 --> 00:46:18,791
you approach about this kind of thing.

871
00:46:18,875 --> 00:46:22,750
Son, if you live in a bubble,
eventually you suffocate.

872
00:46:30,083 --> 00:46:32,083
[indistinct chatter]

873
00:46:35,500 --> 00:46:38,083
Pardon the interruption.
I was wondering if any of you gentlemen

874
00:46:38,166 --> 00:46:42,250
had, uh, possibly seen
our missing dog on your travels?

875
00:46:42,958 --> 00:46:45,166
He disappeared two days ago
on the trail, um,

876
00:46:45,250 --> 00:46:50,041
and if we don't find him within 18 days
and give him his medicine, he could die.

877
00:46:50,125 --> 00:46:51,625
His name is Gonker.

878
00:46:52,875 --> 00:46:55,416
- His name is "Gonkers"?
- "Gonker." Singular.

879
00:46:56,250 --> 00:46:57,791
It's one dog.

880
00:46:57,875 --> 00:46:59,875
[menacing music playing]

881
00:47:00,708 --> 00:47:01,708
Gon-ker.

882
00:47:02,750 --> 00:47:04,125
That's a stupid name.

883
00:47:07,458 --> 00:47:09,625
I gave my dog a stupid name once.

884
00:47:11,666 --> 00:47:12,833
"Macaroni."

885
00:47:14,500 --> 00:47:15,500
Yeah.

886
00:47:16,208 --> 00:47:18,291
He was five when he got out of the yard.

887
00:47:19,791 --> 00:47:20,916
Never came back.

888
00:47:23,791 --> 00:47:25,208
I still dream about him.

889
00:47:26,708 --> 00:47:29,166
What happened to your guy?
How'd he get lost?

890
00:47:30,166 --> 00:47:31,166
Um...

891
00:47:31,875 --> 00:47:33,625
I had him off the leash, so...

892
00:47:34,416 --> 00:47:35,500
Uh, it's my fault.

893
00:47:43,791 --> 00:47:45,583
You need to forgive yourself.

894
00:47:46,541 --> 00:47:49,458
I beat myself up for years
on account of Macaroni.

895
00:47:50,833 --> 00:47:52,041
It does you no good.

896
00:47:52,916 --> 00:47:54,791
And it does no good for Gonkers either.

897
00:47:54,875 --> 00:47:55,875
Gonker.

898
00:47:59,208 --> 00:48:01,291
We've got chapters up and down the coast.

899
00:48:02,291 --> 00:48:05,541
And we'll make sure that every
Asrael's Knight keeps their eyes peeled.

900
00:48:06,916 --> 00:48:08,541
- Oh.
- Thank you.

901
00:48:09,750 --> 00:48:11,375
And thank all the other knights.

902
00:48:11,458 --> 00:48:13,541
Uh, yeah, thanks.

903
00:48:14,500 --> 00:48:15,791
[bikes revving]

904
00:48:21,958 --> 00:48:25,125
[Fielding] No dogs.
Next motel is over 30 miles away,

905
00:48:25,208 --> 00:48:28,458
and their website says,
"No pets over 15 pounds."

906
00:48:28,958 --> 00:48:31,875
All right, let's put his bowls
in your bag.

907
00:48:32,750 --> 00:48:34,375
No, they said, "No dogs."

908
00:48:34,458 --> 00:48:36,666
Yeah. Little laws are for little men.

909
00:48:37,250 --> 00:48:39,375
- The fine is, like, $300.
- Come on.

910
00:48:41,333 --> 00:48:43,208
Ancient trading caravans on the Silk Road

911
00:48:43,291 --> 00:48:45,458
would stop at campgrounds
on their way to the Orient.

912
00:48:45,541 --> 00:48:46,821
You know what they called those?

913
00:48:46,875 --> 00:48:49,041
Holiday Inns that don't allow dogs?

914
00:48:49,125 --> 00:48:50,333
"Caravansaries."

915
00:48:50,416 --> 00:48:52,666
Not only were there camels allowed inside,

916
00:48:53,166 --> 00:48:55,875
the guards would welcome them
and protect them.

917
00:48:55,958 --> 00:48:57,333
- Oh.
- We are a caravansary.

918
00:48:57,416 --> 00:48:59,625
So they are required to welcome our camp.

919
00:48:59,708 --> 00:49:01,083
Come on. Okay.

920
00:49:01,166 --> 00:49:03,625
- [playful music playing]
- Put the coat around me.

921
00:49:03,708 --> 00:49:06,541
- What is this, <i>Scooby-Doo?</i>
- Come on, come on! He's heavy.

922
00:49:10,958 --> 00:49:13,625
Okay, I'm gonna distract the front desk
while you slip by,

923
00:49:13,708 --> 00:49:15,375
and I'll meet you at the elevators.

924
00:49:15,458 --> 00:49:16,666
Let's light this candle.

925
00:49:19,166 --> 00:49:20,666
I am not paying the fine.

926
00:49:20,750 --> 00:49:23,125
Of course not. You'd need money for that.

927
00:49:23,208 --> 00:49:24,833
[phone ringing]

928
00:49:25,875 --> 00:49:26,875
Hello.

929
00:49:26,958 --> 00:49:28,750
<i>[woman] Your dog is with a bad man.</i>

930
00:49:30,541 --> 00:49:31,375
Who is this?

931
00:49:31,458 --> 00:49:34,416
[woman] <i>My neighbor Claude got him.
He got all kinds of animals.</i>

932
00:49:34,500 --> 00:49:36,500
<i>Lord knows what he does to them.</i>

933
00:49:36,583 --> 00:49:40,625
<i>I see lots of dogs get brought in,
but I ain't ever seen one come out.</i>

934
00:49:40,708 --> 00:49:43,583
I don't understand.
She says this guy's harming animals?

935
00:49:43,666 --> 00:49:45,916
That's what she said.
We should call the police.

936
00:49:46,000 --> 00:49:47,333
[Fielding] <i>And tell them what?</i>

937
00:49:47,416 --> 00:49:49,750
They can't enter the guy's house
on an accusation.

938
00:49:49,833 --> 00:49:53,375
They'd need probable cause for a warrant
and there's not enough to get one.

939
00:49:54,791 --> 00:49:56,875
Intro to Constitutional Law, B-plus.

940
00:49:56,958 --> 00:50:00,750
Look, we'll have a conversation
with the guy and we'll see what's what.

941
00:50:00,833 --> 00:50:03,458
- Do we have an address?
- [Ginny] <i>I just texted it to Fielding.</i>

942
00:50:03,541 --> 00:50:06,333
Oh, also, Fields,
um, I need you to get the word out

943
00:50:06,416 --> 00:50:08,833
on my new Twitter and Instagram handles.

944
00:50:08,916 --> 00:50:12,708
It's, um, @RealGonker and @FindGonker.

945
00:50:12,791 --> 00:50:15,291
Hey, you guys be careful
at this Claude fella's.

946
00:50:15,375 --> 00:50:16,958
He might be some kinda serial killer.

947
00:50:17,041 --> 00:50:20,583
Yeah, you're absolutely right. That's why
I'm gonna send Fielding to the front door.

948
00:50:20,666 --> 00:50:22,291
[Ginny laughing] <i>Great.</i>

949
00:50:22,375 --> 00:50:23,833
Be safe. I'm serious.

950
00:50:24,416 --> 00:50:25,250
Bye.

951
00:50:25,333 --> 00:50:27,166
[man] All my paperwork's up-to-date.

952
00:50:27,250 --> 00:50:30,916
I'm fully licensed to act as a non-profit,
temporary shelter for strays.

953
00:50:31,000 --> 00:50:33,708
I'm sorry. My wife called me
and said I should check it out.

954
00:50:33,791 --> 00:50:34,791
I don't know.

955
00:50:34,875 --> 00:50:37,083
It's... No, this isn't
the first time it's happened.

956
00:50:37,166 --> 00:50:41,333
The woman who called, Mrs. Banner,
98 and, uh, losing her faculties.

957
00:50:41,416 --> 00:50:45,000
It's been explained to her a dozen times
what we do, but she just forgets.

958
00:50:45,083 --> 00:50:47,059
- But her heart's in the right place.
- [John] Sure.

959
00:50:47,083 --> 00:50:50,043
- Listen, we're sorry to take up your time.
- You're not taking up my time.

960
00:50:50,125 --> 00:50:54,083
Look, I'm fully plugged in
to the animal rescue community.

961
00:50:54,166 --> 00:50:55,375
I'm gonna scan this, okay?

962
00:50:55,458 --> 00:50:56,750
I'm gonna get a chain going.

963
00:50:56,833 --> 00:51:00,958
We have folks, they spend every weekend
searching for strays just to try and help.

964
00:51:01,041 --> 00:51:02,708
They need to know about Gonker.

965
00:51:02,791 --> 00:51:03,916
Well, thank you.

966
00:51:04,000 --> 00:51:05,000
Yeah, thanks.

967
00:51:05,083 --> 00:51:06,083
You okay?

968
00:51:06,625 --> 00:51:08,000
Oh, yeah, I just...

969
00:51:08,958 --> 00:51:10,916
I was hoping he'd be here, but...

970
00:51:11,500 --> 00:51:12,958
Let's just hope for a miracle.

971
00:51:14,166 --> 00:51:16,166
[somber music playing]

972
00:51:43,250 --> 00:51:46,083
- Ah, good! You got some calories in you.
- [Fielding] Mmm.

973
00:51:46,166 --> 00:51:48,541
Mmm-hmm! Um...

974
00:51:48,625 --> 00:51:53,208
So, I was thinking today
we make our way down to Elkton.

975
00:51:53,291 --> 00:51:54,375
Elkton.

976
00:51:55,166 --> 00:51:57,833
- That's quite a ways.
- Well, we don't have a choice.

977
00:51:57,916 --> 00:51:59,875
It's like we say, Gonker isn't any dog.

978
00:52:01,458 --> 00:52:03,916
As hard as you're searching for him,
he's searching for you.

979
00:52:05,416 --> 00:52:07,625
[man] Hi. Um, so sorry to bother you.

980
00:52:08,208 --> 00:52:11,125
I was wondering,
maybe, if you've seen this dog?

981
00:52:11,208 --> 00:52:13,375
Well, we sure have, 'cause he's our dog.

982
00:52:13,458 --> 00:52:15,625
Hold on. You're the Marshalls?

983
00:52:15,708 --> 00:52:17,625
That's what the mailbox says. And you are?

984
00:52:17,708 --> 00:52:18,708
Um, Tracy.

985
00:52:18,750 --> 00:52:20,125
I can't believe this.

986
00:52:20,208 --> 00:52:24,541
I just read about you guys yesterday,
and it just made me feel so sad.

987
00:52:24,625 --> 00:52:26,958
So I made a bunch of these
to hand out while I hike.

988
00:52:27,041 --> 00:52:28,541
That is incredibly nice of you.

989
00:52:28,625 --> 00:52:32,125
Wow, I guess the <i>Virginia Sun</i>
did us a solid.

990
00:52:32,208 --> 00:52:35,291
The <i>Sun</i>? No, I've read about this
in <i>Roanoke Times.</i>

991
00:52:35,375 --> 00:52:37,583
- Can I see that flyer?
- [Tracy] Yeah, of course.

992
00:52:40,291 --> 00:52:42,333
Ha! This is from the Associated Press.

993
00:52:42,416 --> 00:52:43,875
Gonker's gone national.

994
00:52:44,875 --> 00:52:48,375
- Hello, this is Ginny Marshall.
- Ginny, my name is Alex Olsen.

995
00:52:48,458 --> 00:52:51,458
I saw the article about your dog
in the <i>Duluth News Tribune.</i>

996
00:52:52,041 --> 00:52:54,166
I got a Saint Bernard
with Addison's disease.

997
00:52:54,750 --> 00:52:56,375
<i>I just wanted to let you know</i>

998
00:52:56,458 --> 00:52:58,642
there's certain foods
that you can leave out for Gonker,

999
00:52:58,666 --> 00:53:01,000
that if he can get to 'em,
which might help his condition.

1000
00:53:01,083 --> 00:53:03,333
<i>Give him a few extra days
before his medicine wears off.</i>

1001
00:53:03,833 --> 00:53:05,375
[phone chiming]

1002
00:53:05,458 --> 00:53:06,458
[phone ringing]

1003
00:53:06,541 --> 00:53:08,791
- [phone beeps]
- Hello, this is Ginny Marshall.

1004
00:53:08,875 --> 00:53:10,750
Uh, can you just say that one more time?

1005
00:53:10,833 --> 00:53:12,416
Rhodesian.

1006
00:53:13,000 --> 00:53:14,291
Rhodesian Ridgeback.

1007
00:53:14,375 --> 00:53:15,875
<i>They are excellent trackers.</i>

1008
00:53:15,958 --> 00:53:19,833
<i>But when he goes out to hunt, I have
a method to help him find his way home.</i>

1009
00:53:19,916 --> 00:53:22,666
<i>Take anything you might have
with your son's scent on it.</i>

1010
00:53:22,750 --> 00:53:24,291
<i>Place it outside.</i>

1011
00:53:24,375 --> 00:53:26,708
<i>The scent can carry for up to ten miles.</i>

1012
00:53:26,791 --> 00:53:29,291
- [stirring music playing]
- [phone chiming]

1013
00:53:29,375 --> 00:53:30,875
I can't keep up with all the calls.

1014
00:53:30,958 --> 00:53:34,208
People are reaching out from all over
the world with tips on how to track him,

1015
00:53:34,291 --> 00:53:37,250
how to lure him out of the woods,
how to help him find your scent.

1016
00:53:37,333 --> 00:53:39,708
Well, I don't think
they're gonna need help with that.

1017
00:53:39,791 --> 00:53:40,791
Meaning?

1018
00:53:41,500 --> 00:53:44,166
You're working on kind of a...
patchouli musk.

1019
00:53:45,000 --> 00:53:47,208
- Have you smelled your cologne?
- Aw.

1020
00:53:47,291 --> 00:53:50,333
- Sounds like you two are getting along.
- Oh, no, it's Stockholm syndrome.

1021
00:53:50,416 --> 00:53:53,083
Anyway, I put everyone's tips together
in a Google doc,

1022
00:53:53,166 --> 00:53:55,666
and I just shared it with you.
I sent you a link.

1023
00:53:55,750 --> 00:53:58,416
I recognize your voice,
but you cannot possibly be my mom.

1024
00:53:58,500 --> 00:54:00,583
Ha-ha. Very funny.

1025
00:54:00,666 --> 00:54:03,833
- [stirring music continues]
- [John on megaphone] Gonker!

1026
00:54:05,458 --> 00:54:06,500
[Fielding] Gonker!

1027
00:54:16,750 --> 00:54:19,625
- Man, this is beautiful country.
- Oh, I know.

1028
00:54:20,916 --> 00:54:23,958
I took the youth center kids
on the trail a few times.

1029
00:54:24,958 --> 00:54:26,041
Like, to a stream.

1030
00:54:26,625 --> 00:54:27,625
Kayaked all day.

1031
00:54:29,875 --> 00:54:32,000
- They loved it.
- Sounds like you did too.

1032
00:54:32,791 --> 00:54:33,791
Yeah.

1033
00:54:41,208 --> 00:54:42,208
So you...

1034
00:54:42,291 --> 00:54:45,916
You might think this is,
like, dumb or whatever, but, um...

1035
00:54:48,416 --> 00:54:51,750
I was thinking about maybe
one day working in that field.

1036
00:54:53,958 --> 00:54:55,000
Doing what?

1037
00:54:55,083 --> 00:54:56,291
Uh, you know, like,

1038
00:54:57,333 --> 00:55:00,166
outdoor tours, nature tours,
stuff like that.

1039
00:55:01,041 --> 00:55:02,375
Is there a living in that?

1040
00:55:04,125 --> 00:55:05,375
I don't know.

1041
00:55:07,791 --> 00:55:08,875
Just a thought.

1042
00:55:08,958 --> 00:55:09,958
Ow.

1043
00:55:12,458 --> 00:55:13,583
[Fielding winces]

1044
00:55:14,333 --> 00:55:15,333
[John] Hey!

1045
00:55:16,250 --> 00:55:17,333
Hey, you okay?

1046
00:55:20,333 --> 00:55:22,125
Oh, yeah, it's just some blisters.

1047
00:55:22,208 --> 00:55:25,250
Look, we're a half mile from a rest stop.
Why don't we take a break?

1048
00:55:27,458 --> 00:55:30,500
No, we should keep going.
He's only got two weeks.

1049
00:55:30,583 --> 00:55:32,750
All the more reason
you gotta stay healthy.

1050
00:55:33,250 --> 00:55:35,958
We've got a lot of ground to cover.
Come on.

1051
00:55:49,166 --> 00:55:51,833
Hey. We should
definitely check in with those guys.

1052
00:55:52,500 --> 00:55:55,833
Yeah, I have flyers, and I can recite
the story in my sleep, so...

1053
00:56:01,291 --> 00:56:02,125
Are you coming?

1054
00:56:02,208 --> 00:56:04,750
Thought I'd let you handle it.
Look like your kind of people.

1055
00:56:05,916 --> 00:56:08,416
If you live in a bubble,
you eventually suffocate.

1056
00:56:10,333 --> 00:56:11,416
Now he listens to me.

1057
00:56:12,458 --> 00:56:13,875
[indistinct]

1058
00:56:13,958 --> 00:56:16,625
[man blowing]

1059
00:56:22,083 --> 00:56:23,208
You're gonna hyperventilate.

1060
00:56:23,708 --> 00:56:25,625
See, you got the wrong stuff in there.

1061
00:56:26,250 --> 00:56:29,166
If the kindling bends like this,
it's too wet.

1062
00:56:30,541 --> 00:56:31,875
Unless it breaks,

1063
00:56:33,250 --> 00:56:34,250
it doesn't burn.

1064
00:56:34,916 --> 00:56:36,000
So you need

1065
00:56:37,708 --> 00:56:38,958
more stuff like this.

1066
00:56:42,416 --> 00:56:43,416
See, now...

1067
00:56:45,791 --> 00:56:48,583
- Yeah, that's kindling.
- [man chuckles] Wow.

1068
00:56:48,666 --> 00:56:52,583
- You're, like, full of dad knowledge.
- Ha! I don't know about that.

1069
00:56:52,666 --> 00:56:54,746
Talk to my son,
he'll tell you I'm full of something.

1070
00:56:56,208 --> 00:56:58,375
- He's pretty awesome.
- Fielding?

1071
00:56:58,458 --> 00:56:59,666
Yeah, man.

1072
00:56:59,750 --> 00:57:02,916
Going out on the open road,
searching for his best friend.

1073
00:57:03,000 --> 00:57:05,375
He's got a real loving energy
that's hard to come by.

1074
00:57:05,458 --> 00:57:07,708
It's like you two are on,
like, an epic journey together.

1075
00:57:07,791 --> 00:57:08,791
Like a quest.

1076
00:57:08,833 --> 00:57:10,375
- An epic quest.
- Yo.

1077
00:57:10,458 --> 00:57:12,666
A vision quest, like the movie.

1078
00:57:14,500 --> 00:57:16,250
Matthew Modine, Madonna,

1079
00:57:16,333 --> 00:57:19,208
singing in a Pennsylvania
Appalachian bar? No?

1080
00:57:21,500 --> 00:57:23,833
That's what makes
what you're doing so cool.

1081
00:57:24,333 --> 00:57:26,750
Not many dads
would walk the trail for their kid.

1082
00:57:26,833 --> 00:57:30,750
Yeah. I mean, my old man,
he thinks everything I do is stupid,

1083
00:57:30,833 --> 00:57:34,250
like writing my music, or making my plays.

1084
00:57:34,333 --> 00:57:36,916
No, he doesn't think you're stupid.
He loves you.

1085
00:57:37,583 --> 00:57:40,583
Writing your plays and making your music
isn't gonna pay the bills.

1086
00:57:40,666 --> 00:57:43,375
You know, or get you health care coverage,
so he worries.

1087
00:57:43,458 --> 00:57:45,000
That's what dads do, they...

1088
00:57:45,916 --> 00:57:46,916
[laughs] We worry.

1089
00:57:48,458 --> 00:57:51,625
Mr. Marshall, we were all born in 2000.

1090
00:57:52,291 --> 00:57:54,375
The first humans of the new millennium.

1091
00:57:54,458 --> 00:57:56,041
With technological advances,

1092
00:57:56,125 --> 00:57:59,250
the odds are greater
we'll live past 100 than die before 40.

1093
00:57:59,333 --> 00:58:01,458
So what's the difference
if on our deathbed,

1094
00:58:01,541 --> 00:58:04,541
we had 54 years in the workforce or 53?

1095
00:58:04,625 --> 00:58:06,791
If we die with a little less money
to leave our kids

1096
00:58:06,875 --> 00:58:09,875
but a lot more life experience
and knowledge to pass on?

1097
00:58:10,708 --> 00:58:14,916
Some people know exactly what they want.
And others don't, like me and my friends.

1098
00:58:15,750 --> 00:58:18,375
At the end of the day,
we're all just walking the trail.

1099
00:58:18,458 --> 00:58:23,375
It's just some of us wanna
wait a bit longer before we step off.

1100
00:58:23,458 --> 00:58:24,458
That's all.

1101
00:58:27,000 --> 00:58:29,916
You know, I think my son's been
trying to tell me his version of that,

1102
00:58:30,000 --> 00:58:31,583
like, half a dozen times, and...

1103
00:58:33,083 --> 00:58:34,833
Don't know why I didn't hear it until now.

1104
00:58:36,583 --> 00:58:37,750
'Cause I'm not your son.

1105
00:58:44,208 --> 00:58:46,166
[exhales] All right. This was a good day.

1106
00:58:47,125 --> 00:58:49,291
Just another day
with no dog to show for it.

1107
00:58:50,166 --> 00:58:53,166
Well, people who don't even know us
now know Gonker.

1108
00:58:53,250 --> 00:58:57,583
And the dog can only travel so far,
and the story is now outpacing him.

1109
00:58:57,666 --> 00:59:00,125
So it's a good thing. Believe me.

1110
00:59:03,166 --> 00:59:05,208
- Really? Again?
- [playful music playing]

1111
00:59:08,041 --> 00:59:09,291
Really? All right.

1112
00:59:11,125 --> 00:59:12,125
[grunts]

1113
00:59:13,041 --> 00:59:15,416
This is why I haven't been able
to get much rest.

1114
00:59:15,500 --> 00:59:18,916
I'm so used to Gonker being
in bed with me, I can't sleep without him.

1115
00:59:19,000 --> 00:59:22,500
- Yeah, Well, you're welcome to this one.
- Oh, no, I think he likes you.

1116
00:59:24,750 --> 00:59:26,083
He just won't stop moving.

1117
00:59:28,375 --> 00:59:29,375
Can you stop?

1118
00:59:32,250 --> 00:59:33,541
See if we can pull this off.

1119
00:59:34,791 --> 00:59:36,541
Remember, today was a good day.

1120
00:59:56,958 --> 00:59:58,541
[indistinct coughing]

1121
01:00:06,833 --> 01:00:09,833
- [somber music playing]
- [Yuri whining]

1122
01:00:13,291 --> 01:00:14,875
[heaving]

1123
01:00:18,666 --> 01:00:20,291
[Yuri whining]

1124
01:00:27,250 --> 01:00:28,541
[scratching on door]

1125
01:00:31,541 --> 01:00:32,916
[Fielding groans] It's okay, boy.

1126
01:00:34,833 --> 01:00:35,833
I'm okay.

1127
01:00:46,500 --> 01:00:48,750
Oh! Thanks for all your help, Yuri.

1128
01:00:49,250 --> 01:00:51,083
- [John] So you have enough water?
- Yep.

1129
01:00:51,166 --> 01:00:52,833
- Food?
- PowerBars and beef jerky.

1130
01:00:52,916 --> 01:00:54,958
- You actually gonna eat any of it?
- Yes.

1131
01:00:55,041 --> 01:00:57,541
Good. 'Cause take this in the spirit
with which it's intended,

1132
01:00:57,625 --> 01:00:58,958
but you look like a bag of crap.

1133
01:00:59,041 --> 01:01:01,875
- Thank you very much.
- So you'll take Spotswood up to...

1134
01:01:01,958 --> 01:01:03,358
- To the main trail.
- That's right.

1135
01:01:03,416 --> 01:01:06,291
- And I'll meet you in the parking lot at...
- Browns Gap. Got it.

1136
01:01:06,375 --> 01:01:09,666
It should take you about ten hours
of walking, and I'll see you tonight.

1137
01:01:09,750 --> 01:01:11,583
- Be safe.
- I'll be fine. Promise.

1138
01:01:14,333 --> 01:01:15,791
- See ya.
- [car starting]

1139
01:01:16,958 --> 01:01:17,958
Be good.

1140
01:01:25,291 --> 01:01:27,750
[somber music playing]

1141
01:01:36,375 --> 01:01:37,583
[young Ginny] <i>Oji?</i>

1142
01:01:41,625 --> 01:01:42,791
Oji?

1143
01:01:46,916 --> 01:01:48,208
Oji?

1144
01:01:58,333 --> 01:01:59,333
Where's Oji?

1145
01:02:03,583 --> 01:02:05,625
I need you to be a big girl about this.

1146
01:02:06,708 --> 01:02:09,416
Oji got loose this morning
and ran into Fulton.

1147
01:02:09,500 --> 01:02:11,041
He was struck by a car.

1148
01:02:12,000 --> 01:02:13,083
He didn't make it.

1149
01:02:17,000 --> 01:02:20,833
I'm sorry. I know you liked him,
but these things are a part of life.

1150
01:02:21,625 --> 01:02:25,375
Now, I told your father you would
likely make a big thing about this.

1151
01:02:25,458 --> 01:02:26,541
Prove me wrong.

1152
01:02:26,625 --> 01:02:28,375
Show us that you won't carry on

1153
01:02:28,458 --> 01:02:32,125
and you will be rewarded with
a day of shopping at Josie's Boutique.

1154
01:02:32,625 --> 01:02:35,041
'Cause the truth is, no amount of crying
will bring him back.

1155
01:02:35,125 --> 01:02:37,583
So why waste that energy, okay?

1156
01:02:42,958 --> 01:02:44,958
[somber music playing]

1157
01:03:05,500 --> 01:03:07,166
- [gasps] Oh.
- Ooh.

1158
01:03:07,250 --> 01:03:09,375
- Oh, gosh, you scared me.
- [John chuckles]

1159
01:03:09,458 --> 01:03:10,583
I missed you.

1160
01:03:10,666 --> 01:03:12,875
- I missed you too. What a week.
- [Ginny] Mmm-hmm.

1161
01:03:12,958 --> 01:03:14,125
[John sighs]

1162
01:03:14,208 --> 01:03:15,791
So Yuri's back with Earl,

1163
01:03:15,875 --> 01:03:20,500
and I am so looking forward to a shower
with a regular-sized bar of soap.

1164
01:03:20,583 --> 01:03:21,583
Ugh, I bet. [laughs]

1165
01:03:24,041 --> 01:03:27,125
I don't think I've seen a room like this
since Russell Crowe was doing math.

1166
01:03:27,208 --> 01:03:29,166
Yeah, I've been listening to a podcast

1167
01:03:29,250 --> 01:03:32,166
of the Bushmen in the Kalahari
and how they track antelope,

1168
01:03:32,250 --> 01:03:35,791
and I was thinking there could be
something to that that's applicable here.

1169
01:03:35,875 --> 01:03:36,958
- Sure.
- Yeah.

1170
01:03:37,041 --> 01:03:38,666
And also I've been putting up trackers

1171
01:03:38,750 --> 01:03:41,670
where everybody said that they've
seen Oji, but the description was wrong,

1172
01:03:41,750 --> 01:03:44,875
but I figure maybe if there's a pattern
to his movements, we should follow up.

1173
01:03:44,958 --> 01:03:47,476
Because who knows, maybe every tipster
just described him wrong.

1174
01:03:47,500 --> 01:03:48,580
Yeah, no, that makes sense.

1175
01:03:48,625 --> 01:03:51,916
Yeah, and then there's one other thing.
And you're gonna think I'm crazy.

1176
01:03:52,000 --> 01:03:53,375
- Animal psychics.
- Okay.

1177
01:03:53,916 --> 01:03:55,750
- What?
- No, I'm worried about you.

1178
01:03:56,708 --> 01:03:59,208
I'm fine! There's just
a lot of information coming in,

1179
01:03:59,291 --> 01:04:00,791
and I'm trying to control it all.

1180
01:04:00,875 --> 01:04:02,625
- He's not Oji.
- I'm just trying to...

1181
01:04:03,583 --> 01:04:05,458
- What?
- Gonker is not Oji.

1182
01:04:07,166 --> 01:04:09,500
I know that.
This has nothing to do with Oji.

1183
01:04:09,583 --> 01:04:11,791
You have to stop
putting pressure on yourself.

1184
01:04:15,041 --> 01:04:16,041
It's...

1185
01:04:17,500 --> 01:04:20,125
It's just that
it's happening all over again.

1186
01:04:22,916 --> 01:04:26,833
I promised myself that I would never care
about another dog again,

1187
01:04:26,916 --> 01:04:28,250
and then here I am.

1188
01:04:30,041 --> 01:04:31,833
Heartbroken again.

1189
01:04:32,416 --> 01:04:33,541
Look, look, look, I...

1190
01:04:34,625 --> 01:04:36,875
I promise you it won't happen again.

1191
01:04:38,833 --> 01:04:40,250
We're gonna find this dog.

1192
01:04:40,333 --> 01:04:42,541
- You keep saying that.
- I know.

1193
01:04:43,666 --> 01:04:44,750
Because I believe it.

1194
01:04:52,625 --> 01:04:54,708
[animals chitter]

1195
01:05:02,625 --> 01:05:03,625
[line ringing]

1196
01:05:04,208 --> 01:05:06,648
<i>Hey, it's Fielding.
Sorry I missed your call. Leave a message.</i>

1197
01:05:06,708 --> 01:05:10,000
Look, I am officially beyond worried
to extremely concerned.

1198
01:05:10,083 --> 01:05:12,250
You were supposed to be here
40 minutes ago.

1199
01:05:12,750 --> 01:05:14,750
I'm gonna go
to some of the other trailheads.

1200
01:05:14,833 --> 01:05:17,416
If you end up here,
stay put because I'll be back.

1201
01:05:19,333 --> 01:05:22,476
- [Ginny] <i>Why wouldn't he be answering?</i>
- [John] Reception's spotty on the trail.

1202
01:05:22,500 --> 01:05:24,500
He could have a dead battery or...

1203
01:05:24,583 --> 01:05:25,583
Or what?

1204
01:05:26,250 --> 01:05:29,833
[John sighs] <i>The kid is skin and bones.
He hasn't eaten. He's not sleeping.</i>

1205
01:05:29,916 --> 01:05:32,083
It's dark. He's tired.
I hope he didn't hurt himself.

1206
01:05:32,166 --> 01:05:35,416
I've been up and down this trail.
He's over two hours late.

1207
01:05:35,500 --> 01:05:38,916
- You should have called me sooner!
- Well, I didn't wanna worry you.

1208
01:05:39,000 --> 01:05:40,791
Oh, yeah? How's that working out for ya?

1209
01:05:40,875 --> 01:05:44,291
<i>We've already lost a dog
in these damn woods. And now our son too?</i>

1210
01:05:45,208 --> 01:05:46,208
Hang on.

1211
01:05:46,791 --> 01:05:48,250
I found him! I'll call you back.

1212
01:05:59,916 --> 01:06:00,916
Fielding.

1213
01:06:01,541 --> 01:06:02,791
Where were you?

1214
01:06:02,875 --> 01:06:04,375
I was looking for my dog.

1215
01:06:06,166 --> 01:06:07,166
Come on.

1216
01:06:11,416 --> 01:06:14,291
- [Fielding groans] Watch the heel.
- [John] I got you. Ready?

1217
01:06:15,333 --> 01:06:16,541
Oh, look at this.

1218
01:06:18,583 --> 01:06:20,583
[exhales] Okay. Well,

1219
01:06:21,458 --> 01:06:23,208
twenty-four miles in 12 hours

1220
01:06:24,583 --> 01:06:26,916
on unpaved roads, uphill, downhill.

1221
01:06:27,500 --> 01:06:30,750
- You're pushing yourself to the brink.
- [weakly] I had to cover more ground.

1222
01:06:32,208 --> 01:06:33,333
Gonker needs me.

1223
01:06:38,166 --> 01:06:40,041
Remember the other day you were asking me

1224
01:06:40,125 --> 01:06:42,416
if I was proud
of how you were living your life?

1225
01:06:42,500 --> 01:06:43,750
Your clothes, your choices?

1226
01:06:43,833 --> 01:06:45,500
- Hey, Dad...
- You didn't let me answer.

1227
01:06:45,583 --> 01:06:48,958
- We're cool. We don't have to do all that.
- Hey, hey, hey! Hey, no.

1228
01:06:49,916 --> 01:06:52,291
Will you listen for a minute, okay?
Please.

1229
01:06:52,875 --> 01:06:54,708
I can't take pride in your clothes.

1230
01:06:55,708 --> 01:06:58,375
Okay? I can't take pride
in living in a cabin

1231
01:06:58,458 --> 01:07:01,338
or any of those kind of things
because they're just that, they're things.

1232
01:07:01,416 --> 01:07:03,333
That's not what fathers take pride in.

1233
01:07:05,916 --> 01:07:07,458
I take pride in your character.

1234
01:07:08,625 --> 01:07:12,416
The character that embraces
being kind to everyone.

1235
01:07:14,541 --> 01:07:15,541
It's fun.

1236
01:07:16,708 --> 01:07:17,708
It's funny.

1237
01:07:19,458 --> 01:07:20,375
Loving.

1238
01:07:20,458 --> 01:07:24,333
The kind of character that rescues a puppy
from a shelter and gives it a home.

1239
01:07:24,416 --> 01:07:28,791
The kind of character
that would walk all night on bloody feet

1240
01:07:28,875 --> 01:07:31,041
before it would give up
on someone it loves.

1241
01:07:32,458 --> 01:07:33,458
So,

1242
01:07:34,875 --> 01:07:38,875
you're asking me if I'm proud of you.
I have always been proud of you.

1243
01:07:42,541 --> 01:07:44,041
I wouldn't know how not to be.

1244
01:07:49,750 --> 01:07:51,333
[sniffles]

1245
01:07:52,833 --> 01:07:53,958
I love you, Dad.

1246
01:07:56,708 --> 01:07:57,833
I love you too.

1247
01:08:00,500 --> 01:08:02,500
[sweet music playing]

1248
01:08:08,291 --> 01:08:10,458
Twenty-four miles? That's insane.

1249
01:08:10,541 --> 01:08:14,791
That's what I told him.
But he's not listening. He's dedicated.

1250
01:08:15,750 --> 01:08:16,666
[Ginny] <i>And you?</i>

1251
01:08:16,750 --> 01:08:18,458
Fielding's my compass now.

1252
01:08:19,458 --> 01:08:20,875
<i>Wherever he says we go,</i>

1253
01:08:21,708 --> 01:08:22,625
we go.

1254
01:08:22,708 --> 01:08:24,666
Be safe. I love you.

1255
01:08:24,750 --> 01:08:25,750
<i>[John] Love you.</i>

1256
01:08:26,666 --> 01:08:29,291
[hopeful music playing]

1257
01:08:35,333 --> 01:08:36,666
[Fielding] <i>Almost out of kibble.</i>

1258
01:08:36,750 --> 01:08:39,458
We'll pick some up at town.
It's starting to get dark.

1259
01:08:40,041 --> 01:08:43,125
What if he comes back to the trail
at night and we're not here to find him?

1260
01:08:43,208 --> 01:08:45,489
The experts were telling your mom
if he's anywhere nearby,

1261
01:08:45,541 --> 01:08:47,000
he's gonna pick up your scent.

1262
01:08:47,083 --> 01:08:49,666
I just...
I don't think we've been anywhere nearby.

1263
01:08:50,916 --> 01:08:53,375
- Don't give up hope.
- It's getting hard not to.

1264
01:08:55,416 --> 01:08:56,500
[Nate] Gonker!

1265
01:08:57,000 --> 01:08:58,000
Hello?

1266
01:09:00,208 --> 01:09:02,125
Who's looking for Gonker?

1267
01:09:02,208 --> 01:09:03,208
[Nate] I am!

1268
01:09:04,708 --> 01:09:05,708
Fielding?

1269
01:09:06,500 --> 01:09:07,916
- Nate?
- [Nate] Hey, man!

1270
01:09:08,500 --> 01:09:10,541
Ow! Oh, God. Ow.

1271
01:09:11,458 --> 01:09:12,458
Ow.

1272
01:09:13,875 --> 01:09:17,291
What are you doing off the trail, man?
You could get lost, you could get killed.

1273
01:09:17,375 --> 01:09:20,833
I know! I almost did right there.
Listen. Wasn't my intention.

1274
01:09:20,916 --> 01:09:24,125
I'm not real good
at following all these markers.

1275
01:09:24,208 --> 01:09:29,291
They should make real signs, you know?
Something that says, "Trail that way."

1276
01:09:29,375 --> 01:09:31,083
Dude, what are you doing out here?

1277
01:09:31,166 --> 01:09:32,166
Looking for our dog.

1278
01:09:32,208 --> 01:09:36,125
You said that you guys started north.
I started south, worked my way up.

1279
01:09:36,208 --> 01:09:38,291
Got my walking stick
on account of all the walking.

1280
01:09:38,375 --> 01:09:40,583
Got some donuts
'cause I thought Gonk might smell them.

1281
01:09:40,666 --> 01:09:42,291
Interesting thing about donuts.

1282
01:09:42,375 --> 01:09:44,041
You know who else loves donuts?

1283
01:09:44,125 --> 01:09:47,000
Every freaking bird
in the state of Virginia,

1284
01:09:47,083 --> 01:09:51,041
because I have been mauled
and pecked at and attacked, and it's...

1285
01:09:51,125 --> 01:09:53,125
No, I mean, what are you doing out here?

1286
01:09:56,500 --> 01:09:57,666
This is my fault.

1287
01:10:00,458 --> 01:10:04,083
I'm the one who pointed out
the fox to Gonker, so this is my fault.

1288
01:10:06,750 --> 01:10:09,583
I'm sorry, man. I didn't mean to.
You know that I loved him.

1289
01:10:09,666 --> 01:10:11,666
- I know that you loved him, and we just...
- Nate.

1290
01:10:12,583 --> 01:10:13,625
I never once,

1291
01:10:14,625 --> 01:10:16,666
for a second, ever thought to blame you.

1292
01:10:19,416 --> 01:10:20,416
Like, ever.

1293
01:10:22,791 --> 01:10:25,083
Wish I would have known that,

1294
01:10:26,041 --> 01:10:28,708
because these crows
have been kicking my ass.

1295
01:10:28,791 --> 01:10:31,208
All right. I got an idea.

1296
01:10:32,583 --> 01:10:34,142
- Where's he going?
- Dude, I don't know.

1297
01:10:34,166 --> 01:10:36,291
- God, it's so good to see you.
- Don't touch me, man.

1298
01:10:36,375 --> 01:10:37,375
I know you love me.

1299
01:10:37,416 --> 01:10:39,750
Oh, my God. Mmm. Mmm.

1300
01:10:39,833 --> 01:10:41,833
[lively music playing on jukebox]

1301
01:10:43,625 --> 01:10:44,625
Oh, my God.

1302
01:10:46,916 --> 01:10:47,916
So good.

1303
01:10:49,708 --> 01:10:51,458
Mmm! Oh, my God.

1304
01:10:53,958 --> 01:10:56,333
Did they not feed you
at the psych department, Nate?

1305
01:10:58,000 --> 01:11:01,125
It's more of a food for the soul
kind of group, you know?

1306
01:11:01,208 --> 01:11:03,267
I'm thinking about selling out,
going to Wall Street.

1307
01:11:03,291 --> 01:11:07,208
Wow! Yeah? What about
becoming a "philosophical artist"?

1308
01:11:07,708 --> 01:11:09,000
"I love capitalism."

1309
01:11:09,083 --> 01:11:10,833
"It rewards me for being brave,

1310
01:11:10,916 --> 01:11:14,583
and it awards me for being innovative
and thinking outside the box."

1311
01:11:14,666 --> 01:11:17,291
Henry Rollins.
And he was a philosophical artist.

1312
01:11:17,375 --> 01:11:19,708
Maybe I'll become
an organic farmer or something.

1313
01:11:19,791 --> 01:11:22,583
- I don't know. Weighing both options.
- You're strange, Nate.

1314
01:11:23,541 --> 01:11:26,125
And I love it.
All right, I'm gonna go hit the head.

1315
01:11:28,458 --> 01:11:31,083
Papa seems like
he's in a fine mood tonight.

1316
01:11:31,166 --> 01:11:33,458
How you guys getting along,
all this time together?

1317
01:11:34,416 --> 01:11:35,416
Um...

1318
01:11:35,875 --> 01:11:39,666
Good. Really good.
Yeah, I think we found our rhythm.

1319
01:11:40,333 --> 01:11:42,059
- [woman] Can I clear these?
- Yes, thank you.

1320
01:11:42,083 --> 01:11:43,541
- Uh, yeah, thank you.
- [tutting]

1321
01:11:43,625 --> 01:11:45,625
- You didn't go near your burger.
- I know.

1322
01:11:47,375 --> 01:11:48,500
Thank you.

1323
01:11:49,083 --> 01:11:50,416
What's up with that?

1324
01:11:51,083 --> 01:11:53,041
Just don't bring that up
in front of my dad.

1325
01:11:53,125 --> 01:11:53,958
Okay.

1326
01:11:54,041 --> 01:11:56,583
It's just my stomach's been upset.

1327
01:11:56,666 --> 01:11:59,041
It was messed up last semester of school.

1328
01:11:59,708 --> 01:12:02,416
Fields, you gotta get that checked.
It could be who knows what?

1329
01:12:02,500 --> 01:12:05,916
- [waitress] Another beer?
- None for me, thank you. I am driving.

1330
01:12:06,000 --> 01:12:07,800
I'll have another water
when you get a chance.

1331
01:12:07,875 --> 01:12:11,833
Um, also if there's any way you could hang
this up by the door, maybe on that board.

1332
01:12:11,916 --> 01:12:13,875
Otherwise, I totally understand.
It's fine.

1333
01:12:13,958 --> 01:12:15,000
Your dog's lost?

1334
01:12:15,708 --> 01:12:17,958
Oh, my goodness! He's so cute!

1335
01:12:18,958 --> 01:12:21,541
- No worries. I'll do it myself.
- Thank you. Really.

1336
01:12:21,625 --> 01:12:23,625
"Nothing for me. I'm driving."

1337
01:12:23,708 --> 01:12:24,708
[man laughs]

1338
01:12:25,500 --> 01:12:28,500
<i>♪ I'm Little Bo-Peep and I lost my puppy ♪</i>

1339
01:12:28,583 --> 01:12:30,541
I'm sorry, is this high school?

1340
01:12:30,625 --> 01:12:31,541
Just ignore it.

1341
01:12:31,625 --> 01:12:34,375
[man] <i>♪ Where, oh, where
Has my little dog gone? ♪</i>

1342
01:12:34,458 --> 01:12:36,875
<i>♪ Where, oh, where could he be? ♪</i>

1343
01:12:36,958 --> 01:12:40,166
You spoiled college guys go on the trail.

1344
01:12:40,250 --> 01:12:44,458
You don't know what the hell you're doing.
That's why you lost your stupid dog.

1345
01:12:44,541 --> 01:12:47,375
Hey, I've had a hell of a week and a half.

1346
01:12:47,458 --> 01:12:48,291
Uh...

1347
01:12:48,375 --> 01:12:52,041
- So if you two idiots could shut up?
- Don't...

1348
01:12:52,125 --> 01:12:53,125
[man] Okay.

1349
01:12:53,166 --> 01:12:54,458
Oh, my God.

1350
01:12:54,541 --> 01:12:56,666
- You got something to say?
- [Nate] Mmm-mmm.

1351
01:12:58,625 --> 01:12:59,791
Say it to my face.

1352
01:12:59,875 --> 01:13:03,583
Oh, no, I already had to hear you.
Now you want me to look at you too?

1353
01:13:03,666 --> 01:13:05,250
Oh, my God! Shut up!

1354
01:13:06,208 --> 01:13:07,625
[John] Whoa, whoa, whoa.

1355
01:13:07,708 --> 01:13:10,041
I wasn't aware there was dancing
at this establishment.

1356
01:13:10,125 --> 01:13:12,208
- Doesn't concern you, Pops.
- [John] Ha!

1357
01:13:12,291 --> 01:13:14,708
Yeah, well, that's where you're wrong.
See, this is my son.

1358
01:13:14,791 --> 01:13:16,291
- Dad.
- And that is his friend.

1359
01:13:16,375 --> 01:13:19,291
So it is my biological edict
to protect 'em.

1360
01:13:19,375 --> 01:13:21,125
What do you think
you're gonna do about it?

1361
01:13:23,125 --> 01:13:24,583
Well, that's a fair question.

1362
01:13:25,833 --> 01:13:27,750
You see, I think for a living.

1363
01:13:27,833 --> 01:13:30,458
Anywhere there's a problem
around the world,

1364
01:13:30,541 --> 01:13:31,916
I look at the facts on the ground,

1365
01:13:32,000 --> 01:13:34,200
and then I make
what's called a "predictive assumption."

1366
01:13:34,708 --> 01:13:37,041
And here's my assessment
of the facts right now.

1367
01:13:37,625 --> 01:13:39,250
That you've had a couple drinks,

1368
01:13:39,791 --> 01:13:41,250
you're looking to have a fight.

1369
01:13:41,333 --> 01:13:44,833
These two are not. So now you're thinking
maybe you'll take a run at me.

1370
01:13:44,916 --> 01:13:46,708
- 100%.
- Yeah, well.

1371
01:13:47,541 --> 01:13:48,791
Here's what's gonna happen.

1372
01:13:49,375 --> 01:13:50,750
I'm gonna take my thumb

1373
01:13:52,208 --> 01:13:55,708
and jam it so far into your eye socket
it could pop it out like a cork.

1374
01:13:57,083 --> 01:14:00,083
So now it's your turn to think,
is it worth the risk?

1375
01:14:00,875 --> 01:14:04,083
Because if it's not,
then you better back off.

1376
01:14:04,750 --> 01:14:06,750
[tense music playing]

1377
01:14:10,875 --> 01:14:12,250
Y'all ain't worth the hassle.

1378
01:14:29,958 --> 01:14:32,416
The cheeseburger was fantastic.

1379
01:14:38,791 --> 01:14:40,833
He's Dwayne Johnson in Dockers.

1380
01:14:43,541 --> 01:14:45,000
[Ginny on phone] <i>They found him!</i>

1381
01:14:45,083 --> 01:14:47,583
<i>A yellow lab mix
was brought into a shelter really weak.</i>

1382
01:14:47,666 --> 01:14:50,500
<i>Blood tests show he has Addison's disease.</i>

1383
01:14:51,541 --> 01:14:53,541
[dramatic music playing]

1384
01:15:10,125 --> 01:15:11,458
All right, here we go!

1385
01:15:15,291 --> 01:15:16,416
You okay?

1386
01:15:16,500 --> 01:15:17,500
Yeah.

1387
01:15:18,541 --> 01:15:19,666
Just wanna get my dog.

1388
01:15:20,625 --> 01:15:23,000
We will have him soon enough.

1389
01:15:26,666 --> 01:15:29,166
We had heard about Gonker on the news.

1390
01:15:29,250 --> 01:15:33,500
And when the vet said he had Addison's,
oh, we were so excited to call you guys.

1391
01:15:33,583 --> 01:15:34,583
Here.

1392
01:15:45,666 --> 01:15:46,666
It's not him.

1393
01:15:48,583 --> 01:15:52,541
I don't... I don't understand.
It looks just like the dog on the flyer.

1394
01:15:53,125 --> 01:15:56,750
He's a little smaller and has reddish fur.

1395
01:15:59,875 --> 01:16:01,500
Thank you. Thank you.

1396
01:16:01,583 --> 01:16:03,583
[somber music playing]

1397
01:16:19,791 --> 01:16:20,625
Oh, Fielding.

1398
01:16:20,708 --> 01:16:22,708
[crying]

1399
01:16:36,250 --> 01:16:38,250
[emotional music playing]

1400
01:17:05,791 --> 01:17:07,291
I'm so sorry, Gonker.

1401
01:17:09,541 --> 01:17:10,625
[sighs]

1402
01:17:39,750 --> 01:17:40,750
[mutters]

1403
01:17:44,750 --> 01:17:46,041
No. Oh, no.

1404
01:17:53,791 --> 01:17:55,750
Dad, what are we doing?
We have to keep looking.

1405
01:17:55,833 --> 01:17:56,958
Say hello to your mother.

1406
01:17:57,041 --> 01:17:58,601
- You look terrible!
- We can't give up.

1407
01:17:58,666 --> 01:17:59,875
He's gonna die out there.

1408
01:17:59,958 --> 01:18:02,583
- Honey, odds are he's already gone.
- Don't say that.

1409
01:18:02,666 --> 01:18:05,875
- I found your sandwich. You didn't eat it.
- I don't care about that.

1410
01:18:05,958 --> 01:18:09,208
Fielding, we have had over
a hundred people trying to find Gonker,

1411
01:18:09,291 --> 01:18:10,583
and he still hasn't turned up.

1412
01:18:10,666 --> 01:18:13,125
[voice breaking] You're not sleeping,
and you're not eating,

1413
01:18:13,208 --> 01:18:15,416
and the stress is taking its toll on you.

1414
01:18:15,500 --> 01:18:17,791
We need to keep looking.

1415
01:18:18,291 --> 01:18:19,916
It's over, baby.

1416
01:18:28,083 --> 01:18:29,791
He was the best friend I ever had.

1417
01:18:29,875 --> 01:18:31,125
I know.

1418
01:18:33,208 --> 01:18:35,125
I know exactly how you feel.

1419
01:18:49,166 --> 01:18:51,250
[wincing]

1420
01:18:52,541 --> 01:18:57,958
[phone ringing]

1421
01:19:00,083 --> 01:19:01,583
- Hi.
- [Peyton] <i>Hey.</i>

1422
01:19:01,666 --> 01:19:03,166
<i>Um, Mom and Dad filled me in.</i>

1423
01:19:03,250 --> 01:19:04,250
How you holding up?

1424
01:19:05,250 --> 01:19:06,250
[Fielding] <i>I'm not.</i>

1425
01:19:06,708 --> 01:19:08,583
You did everything you could, Fields.

1426
01:19:09,333 --> 01:19:11,458
[Fielding] <i>All I could
would mean I'm still out there.</i>

1427
01:19:11,541 --> 01:19:12,583
You're sick.

1428
01:19:12,666 --> 01:19:15,375
As hard as it may be,
you need to take a step back.

1429
01:19:15,958 --> 01:19:17,625
Gonker didn't make me like this.

1430
01:19:20,250 --> 01:19:22,250
I've been feeling sick
for a few months now.

1431
01:19:23,458 --> 01:19:25,375
